<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Sudanese President Omar Bashir inaugurated Sudan's
oil exports Monday by initiating an oil tanker carrying 600,000
barrels of oil bought by the multi-national Shell company.
</P>
<P>
The tanker, setting sail from Sudan's Red Sea port city of
Bashayer, will arrive in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference, Sudanese Minister of Energy and
Mining Awad Ahmed el-Jaz said the coming phase will witness the
completion of the oil refining project at the Al Obayid refinery.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili
said the volume of Egyptian-Syrian trade in 1998 was 76.4 million
U.S. dollars, an increase of 44.2 percent over 1997.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade during the period from January to March
1999 was 16.1 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's Al Ahram daily quoted the minister as saying that the
balance of trade between Egypt and Syria has been in Egypt's favor
from 1992 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
The value of Egyptian exports to Syria in 1998 was 45.6 million
dollars as compared to 34.6 million dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the value of Egyptian imports from Syria in 1998
stood at 30.7 million dollars, as compared to 18.4 million dollars
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The board of directors of the Alexandria free zone has
approved 14 new industrial investment projects with a total
capital of 450 million dollars and a total investment cost of 174
million dollars, Tuesday's Al Ahram said.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Alexandria Governor Mohamed Salam Mahgoub
as saying that the projects are financed by investors from
Britain, Italy, Greece, Denmark, Spain, France and Finland.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The economic and commercial section of the Dutch
embassy in Cairo has disclosed that the volume of trade between
Egypt and the Netherlands had grown by 10 percent during the past
year.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the volume of Egyptian exports to the
Netherlands amounted to more than 500 million Egyptian pounds (147
million U.S. dollars) while Egyptian imports stood at 1.8 billion
Egyptian pounds (529 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
