<HEADLINE> Annan Hails Congolese Rebels' Signing of Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Tuesday extended a welcome to the signing of a peace
accord on Congo (K) by rebels in the African country.
</P>
<P>
A statement, issued by the spokesman here, said, "the
Secretary-General welcomes the signing of the Lusaka ceasefire
agreement on the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) by the
Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD), which took place in Lusaka
today."
</P>
<P>
"The signing of the Agreement by the RCD, the Congolese
Liberation Movement and all Governments concerned should clear the
way for the timely implementation of the ceasefire agreement
enhances the peace and security of the region and facilities the
long-awaited international support towards national recovery," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General underlines the importance of ensuing the
provision of food aid and the reestablishment of essential
services such as health, safe water and education in the DRC,"
said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Annan "calls on all Government officials and rebel
representatives to ensure safe and unhindered access for all U.N.
and related personnel throughout the DRC," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"He also calls upon the donor community to respond generously
to the humanitarian interagency appeal and resource mobilization
for the peacekeeping and related efforts," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General commends the efforts fo President
Frederick Chiluba (of Zambia) and all the other leaders concerned
for the efforts they continue to make to peacefully resolve the
conflict in the DRC," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"He reiterates his call on all belligerents to honor their
commitment to implement the ceasefire and facilitate the early
commencement of the national dialogue on the political future of
the country," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"He stresses the readiness of the United Nations to continue to
work closely with the regional countries and the OAU in the common
effort to bring a negotiated settlement to the conflict in the
DRC," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Congolese rebel leaders Tuesday signed a ceasefire agreement in
Lusaka, capital of Zambia, to end the year-long civil war in the
central African country, raising hopes for peace in Africa's
biggest multinational conflict.
</P>
<P>
Fifty founding members of the rebel group, Congolese Rally for
Democracy, took part in the signing ceremony, ending six weeks of
wrangling over whose names should appear on the agreement, reports
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
