<HEADLINE> World Bank Lends 44.5 Million Dollars to Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved
Tuesday a loan of 44.5 million U.S. dollars to Romania to finance
a Mine Closure and Social Mitigation Project designed to reduce
the burden of national budget by permanently closing 29 uneconomic
mines.
</P>
<P>
The project marks the first phase in the restructuring of the
Romanian mining sector and is essentially a mine-focused regional
social mitigation project, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The money also will be used to support the government's efforts
to revitalize depressed mining areas through investments for
support of small enterprises, re-training, and job creation
through a more diversified local economy.
</P>
<P>
Total project cost is 61.5 million dollars. Financing would
also include 12.8 million dollars from the Romanian government and
4.2 million dollars from the Department for International
Development of Britain.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank loan will be at the bank's standard interest
rate for LIBOR-based single-currency loans, repayable in 20 years,
including a 5-year grace period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
