<HEADLINE> UK Consumer Confidence on the Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- British consumers are more
optimistic about the economy, though they are still reluctant to
spend money on a large purchase, according to a survey published
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, carried out by business consultancy GfK Great
Britain, found that 27 percent of the consumers now expect the
general economic situation to improve over the next twelve months,
compareed with 23 percent last month.
</P>
<P>
That was against 24 percent who expected the situation to
deteriorate over the coming year. In July, 28 percent of those
surveyed had expected the situation to deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
But although consumers are more confident about the economy,
they are less likely to spend their money on a large purchase.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of those surveyed who believe that now is a good
time to buy a major item, such as a TV or a washing machine, has
fallen, for the third consecutive month, to 28 percent. This
follows a figure of 30 percent last month.
</P>
<P>
But GfK still expects a slight increase in high street spending
as those surveyed said their household finances had improved.
</P>
<P>
Of the people interviewed, 28 percent said their household
finances had improved, an increase of 8 percent year-on-year - and
31 percent expect their household finances to rise over the coming
year, a jump of 9 percent year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
And, for the fourth consecutive month, savings intentions
dropped to the lowest level since December 1996. GfK report said
"it would seem fair to draw the conclusion that increased personal
prosperity combined with dwindling saving intentions will lead to
a slight increase in high street expenditure over the coming
months, despite little enthusiasm from consumers."
</P>
<P>
The survey of 2,000 individuals in the United Kingdom was
carried out by GfK on behalf of the European Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
