<HEADLINE> Dutch Government Opens Internet Site on Fines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands has opened a
Internet site about fines to allow the public to look at all kinds
of minor offences, especially road-traffic related regulations,
the Dutch government said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The "Fines Database", or Boetebase, was set up on Internet by
the Public Prosecution Service. "This will enable members of the
public to check the sanctions applied by the Public Prosecution
Service or the police for a large number of minor offences," the
government said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
The database covers about 600 commonly committed minor
offences, which are divided into several categories. Main
categories are road and water traffic offences, environmental
offences, drink-related offences and offences concerning fresh
water fishing.
</P>
<P>
A long list of fines can be found on the Internet, including
speeding fines, penalties for things such as driving with an
invalid driving licence, putting out home trash too early and
fishing without a permit.
</P>
<P>
In the low land country with population of about 15 million,
more than 5.2 million fines were imposed in 1998 for road traffic
offences alone, including over 3.4 million for speeding offences,
almost 900,000 for parking infringements and 227,000 fines for
running red traffic lights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
