<HEADLINE> Annan Strongly Condemns Killing of Civilians in Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Tuesday strongly condemned rebels' killing of
civilians, including women and children, in the capital Bujumbura,
and called on rebels to end all attacks against civilians.
</P>
<P>
A statement, issued here by a spokesman, said, "The
Secretary-General learned with great distress of the murderous
attacks committed on August 28 and 29 by rebels in Burundi on the
capital city of Bujumbura and which were directed against
civilians living in Mutanga North and Musaga."
</P>
<P>
"As a result, many innocent civilians, including women and
children, were killed and property destroyed," the statement said.
"The Secretary-General strongly condemns these acts and reiterates
his call on the rebels to end all attacks against civilians and
abide by international and human rights norms."
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Hutu rebels attacked the capital in brutal overnight
raids, murdering 38 civilians and taking on the army in fierce
fighting that killed another 20 people, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Burundi has been locked in a series of ethnic conflicts between
the Hutu majority and Tutsi minority over the past three decades.
About 150,000 people, most of them civilians, have been killed
since civil war again erupted in 1993.  
</P>
</TEXT>
