<HEADLINE> Accidents Leading Cause of Childhood Death in EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Accidental injuries are the
leading cause of childhood deaths in European Union countries,
British researchers said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Around 4,500 deaths, a third of all deaths in children, are
caused by accidental injury every in EU countries, Anita Morrison,
of the University of Glasgow, said in a report published in the
British journal Injury Prevention.
</P>
<P>
The data, which covered the period 1984 to 1993 for children up
to the age of 14, are taken from the World Health Organization
(WHO) and national government agencies.
</P>
<P>
Anita Morrison and her colleagues found that the principal
causes of accidental childhood death in EU countries were the
result of injuries caused by road traffic accidents, which
accounts for almost half of all such deaths.
</P>
<P>
Drownings were the second most common cause of death,
particularly in Northern Europe, followed by fires and falls.
</P>
<P>
Almost a third of injuries were classified as "other", and
included deaths from poisoning, suffocation, wounds and the
adverse effects of medicines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
