<HEADLINE> Egypt Reiterates Support for Unity of Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Deputy Prime Minister
Youssef Wali on Tuesday reiterated his country's support for
Sudan's unity.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with John Garang, leader of the rebel Sudan
People's Liberation Army (SPLA), Wali said Cairo supports all
efforts aimed at realizing stability and unity of Sudan, the
Middle East News Agency (MENA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Wali discussed with Garang the situation in Sudan and an
Egyptian-Libyan initiative to help bring an end to the civil war
in Sudan and reach national conciliation in the country, MENA said.
</P>
<P>
Garang's SPLA has been fighting for 16 years for greater
autonomy for Christians and animists in southern states. Nearly 2
million people have died in the war and the ensuing famine.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has expressed keenness on helping the southern neighbor
realize peace through political means and has been mediating
between the Sudanese government and the opposition in the recent
two years.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Libya proposed a five-point plan early this month,
calling for permanent cease-fire in Sudan and holding a national
reconciliation conference.
</P>
<P>
The plan was welcomed by the Sudanese government and the
opposition political parties within the National Democratic
Alliance, which includes SPLA, but was rejected by Garang.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader demanded that the government freeze the 1998
constitution, lift the state of emergency, free political
prisoners and restore freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
Garang arrived in Cairo on Monday to discuss with Sadiq
al-Mahdi, former Sudanese prime minister and leader of the Umma
party, his rejection of the Egyptian-Libyan plan. Al-Mahdi lives
in exile in Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
