<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Discover New Way to Treat Obesity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- A novel method discovered by
scientists in the United States could lead to new pharmaceutical
treatments for overweight people worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The finding, published in the September issue of Nature
Medicine, an international science journal, is a dramatic
departure from most current obesity research, which concentrates
on controlling appetite.
</P>
<P>
This new approach, developed by scientists at the U.S. National
Institute of Mental Health, centers on the way in which the body
stores and burns fat.
</P>
<P>
The finding is tied to a gene known as POMC, found in both mice
and humans which provides signals that are important both during
development and also later in life.
</P>
<P>
The researchers were originally studying the impact of POMC on
the development of the brain when they discovered it also played a
major role in weight regulation.
</P>
<P>
Their research showed that mice lacking POMC-derived signals
were obese and exhibited rapid weight gain, increased food intake
and other similar physiological characteristics to POMC-deficient
humans.
</P>
<P>
When the scientists treated obese mice with a hormone made by
the POMC gene, called MSH, the mice returned to almost normal
weight in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to do follow-up research in mice and the results
are promising so far," said Brennan, one of the researchers, in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to pair up with a strategic partner that will help
move this study in to human clinical trials," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
