<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Producer Inflation, Money Supply Ease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 31 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's producer
price index (PPI) showed an annual rate of increase of 6.2 in July
this year, 0.2 percentage point lower than in June.
</P>
<P>
Its broad-based M3 money supply rose by 2.5 billion rand or 0.6
percent in July, after a sharp increase of 10.3 billion rand in
June.
</P>
<P>
The figures were released by Statistics South Africa and the
South African Reserve Bank (SARB) respectively on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The higher-than-expected increases in the M3 money supply and
the PPI do not augur well for interest rates in the medium term,
South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted an economist as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"Bond markets do not like the sign of increased PPI inflation
as it may suggest that producers are confronted with cost-push
pressures and therefore are likely to pass them on to the
consumer," said James Theledi, senior economist at Gensec Asset
Management.
</P>
<P>
"Given the 13-cent-per-liter increase in the petrol price which
is likely to add 0.3 percent to the PPI for September, the markets
will view the recent data as very disappointing and bearish for
interest rates," he said.
</P>
<P>
Theledi said that the higher-than-expected increase in money
supply growth was due mainly to the foreign exchange inflows
generated largely by Old Mutual's demutualization in July this
year.
</P>
<P>
"Money supply growth is expected to trend downwards in the
coming months to reflect the weak economy and remain close to the
bottom of the SARB's target range of 6 to 10 percent," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The fall in private sector credit extension (which is the main
driver of growth in the money supply) in July is consistent with
the sluggish economy."
</P>
<P>
Annual growth in private sector credit extension slowed
significantly in July to 9.42 percent from 11.43 percent in June,
according to the SARB. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
