<HEADLINE> U.S. Concerned With Y2K Impact on Angola Civil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Potential information chaos at
the turn of the millennium in Angola's civil aviation sector
should be given more attention, U.S. ambassador to Angola said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Aware of the disastrous influence of Y2k, or called "millenium
bug", on the aviation sector, Joseph Sullivan expressed his
anxiety when he met with Angola's Vice Minister of Science and
Technology Pedro Teta.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Teta, also head of an inter-ministerial
commission responsible for eliminating the Y2K, informed the U.S.
ambassador of the progress made by his commission, especially in
the civil aviation sector, according to local press.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ambassador said that his country has been
collaborating with Angola, furnishing useful equipment, for
example some "cd roms", for preventing the "bug" from rioting.
</P>
<P>
He also considered the meeting with Teta as a good opportunity
for talking about the Y2K problem which results from shortsighted
computer design.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government said in early June that the country had
to spend 200 million U.S. dollars to remove the "bug", which will
probably threaten the country's most sectors including
telecommunications, civil aviation, financial sectors and banks.
</P>
