<HEADLINE> Iraqi Deputy Premier Meets With U.S. Congressional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The meeting with Iraqi Deputy
Prime Minister Tariq Aziz on Tuesday was "helpful and important,"
a visiting U.S. congressman said.
</P>
<P>
A member of the U.S. congressional delegation, who asked not be
named, told reporters that the meeting was "helpful and
important," adding the U.S. congressional delegation stressed at
the meeting that their visit to Iraq is not state-to-state
political visit, rather it is an "independent" visit.
</P>
<P>
Aziz reportedly said during the meeting that the sufferings of
the Iraqi people were caused by the U.S. policy toward Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation said they make the visit to Iraq in order
to know what they can do to help lift the United Nations sanctions
imposed on Iraq following its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The eight-member delegation of U.S. congressional aides arrived
in Baghdad on Sunday to investigate the effect of U.N. sanctions
imposed on Iraq for nine years.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that a U.S. congressional delegation
visits Iraq after the country was put under U.N. economic
sanctions in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival in Baghdad, the delegation said they would
examine the effect of economic sanctions on the Iraqi civilian
population, Iraqi government policy and U.S. economic and
strategic interests.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation will also investigate the effects of
depleted uranium, the health hazards suffered by U.S. veterans and
Iraqi civilians, as well as the escalating U.S. bombing campaign
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has blamed the U.N. sanctions for the deaths of hundreds
of thousands of Iraqis through malnutrition and the collapse of
medical services.
</P>
<P>
Iraq Health Undersecretary Shawqi Murqus on Monday met the
U.S. congressional delegation after the delegation visited a
children hospital in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Murqus reviewed the health situation of
the Iraqi people due to shortage in medicine and medical
appliances.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey conducted by the United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) found that child mortality rates have more than
doubled in south and central Iraq since the sanctions were in
place.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF officials have estimated that some 5000-6000 Iraqi
children under the age of five die each month due to malnutrition
and various curable diseases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
