<HEADLINE> World Bank Agrees to Finance Egyptian Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has agreed to
provide Egypt with a total of 320 million U.S. dollars in the
current and coming fiscal years to finance some of the country's
projects, a bank senior official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Khaled Akram, head of the World Bank's Egypt department, told
the country's Middle East News Agency that 120 million dollars
will be made available during the current fiscal year starting on
July 1.
</P>
<P>
This sum of money will be used in the building of sewage
projects throughout Egypt, Akram said. Large parts of Egypt,
including lower income Cairo neighborhoods, remain without sewage
systems.
</P>
<P>
The bank will offer the additional 200 million dollars in the
next fiscal year for projects aimed at boosting the country's
higher education system and training the workforce, Akram said.
</P>
<P>
Financing for the two projects would be made available through
a number of European agencies and include low-interest, long-term
loans, he said, without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank official said the Egyptian government pursues a
cautious policy based on restriction of foreign loans except for
dire necessity.
</P>
<P>
The bank, which maintains a close cooperation relationship with
Egypt, is ready to study any Egyptian projects that needs finance
because of the strong foundations of the country's economy, Akram
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
