<HEADLINE> Israeli, German Officials to Meet Over Aviation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 31 (Xinhua) - Israeli officials will visit
Germany next week to find a solution to the aviation dispute over
adding Lufthansa airline's flights to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Local economic daily Globes reported on Tuesday that the
Israeli delegation led by Avner Yarkoni, chief of Israeli Civil
Aviation Authority, will also include representatives of the
Israeli national airline El Al.
</P>
<P>
The dispute arose after Israeli Civil Aviation Authority
decided recently that Lufthansa airline will not be permitted to
increase its activity until a solution is found to the matter of
discrimination against El Al passengers in security checks at
Frankfurt International Airport.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Aviation Authority and El Al claim that Lufthansa
passengers travelling from Germany to Israel are subjected to
less stringent checks than that of El Al passengers at the
airport.
</P>
<P>
In response, Lufthansa claims it is not involved in security
regulations at German airports, and there is no reason, therefore,
to prevent it increasing its activity to and from Israel.
</P>
<P>
Lufthansa is seeking to operate eighteen weekly flights, an
addition of three weekly flights compared to its current activity.
</P>
<P>
In the year 2000, the company plans to operate twenty-one
flights on this route.
</P>
<P>
Lufthansa has reported an increase in the number of passengers
to Israel since the start of the year, and a large order backlog
for the winter season.
</P>
<P>
Due to the full occupancy of its flights, Lufthansa claims it
has been forced to reject requests from tourist groups to reach
Israel by its flights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
