<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last Congo Rebel Factions Sign Truce Pact in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Prospects of peace have finally
dawned on the Democratic Republic of the Congo as the last rebel
factions append their signatures to a cease-fire agreement in
Lusaka Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 46 founder members of the main rebel group, the Congolese
Rally for Democracy (RCD), signed the peace agreement in a
compromise solution after a split between two rival factions
threatened to derail the entire peace process.
</P>
<P>
The peace agreement, reached in Lusaka on July 10 by six
countries directly involved in the conflict in the Congo, calls
for a cease-fire to begin within 24 hours of the signing ceremony
and the formation of a joint military commission to monitor the
accord and demobilize several irregular militia armies scattered
in eastern Congo or former Zaire, the third largest country in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
It also calls for the creation of a unified army and a national
dialog on the battered country's political future.
</P>
<P>
The rebel groups could not sign the peace pact because of
internal leadership wrangles in the RCD while the other rebel
group, the Movement for the Liberation of the Congo (MLC) led by
Pierre Bemba, signed the agreement early this month.
</P>
<P>
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba chaired the signing
ceremony, which was overseen by representatives from the Congo,
South Africa, Rwanda, Uganda, Gabon, Zimbabwe, Namibia, Mauritius,
Tanzania, Chairman of the Joint Military Commission (JMC) Rachid
Lalli, as well as the United Nations, Southern Africa Development
Community (SADC), Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa
(COMESA), Organization of Africa Unity (OAU) and the European
Union (EU). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
