<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Confidence Falls Again in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Consumer Confidence Index
fell for the second straight month in August as more Americans got
concerned with higher interest rates, the Conference Board, the
U.S. prominent research group, said in a report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The index declined 0.4 of a point to 135.8 from a revised 136.2
in July. The July figure originally was reported as 135.6.
</P>
<P>
"Hikes in interest, severe drought conditions in the Northeast,
and rising gasoline prices have helped dampen overall consumer
optimism," said Lynn Franco, Director of the Board's Consumer
Research Center. The Federal Reserve raised interest rates twice
in the past months in a bid to preempt inflation from the U.S.
economy.
</P>
<P>
But Franco said, "these latest dips in confidence are not of
great concern. Confidence in the future remains high and the
consumer shopping spree continues, with consumer spending having
generaled virtually all U.S. economic growth during the first six
months of this year."
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board said consumers are less confident about
both current economic conditions and jobs than they were in July.
But this slight decline in confidence did not carry over into
consumers' expectations for the next six months, it said.
</P>
<P>
About 17 percent of all consumers look for business conditions
to get better, roughly the same figure recorded last month, the
Board said, adding that about 17.5 percent expect the job market
to improve during the next six months, up from 16 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
Consumer sentiment is an important economic indicator because
consumer spending accounts for about two-third of the U.S. overall
economic activity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
