<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Wheat Trade in 1999/2000 to Increase 5%: IGC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 31 (Xinhua) - Increased demand in East Asia and
North Africa, caused by sharply reduced harvests, is expected to
contribute to a 5 percent increase in world wheat trade in
1999/2000, according to a report by International Grains Council
(IGC).
</P>
<P>
Total shipments are expected to rise to 100.1 m.tons, up from
95.6 m. The figure is 1.6 m. above the July projection, largely
due to increased forecasts for Brazil, India and South Korea, IGC
said.
</P>
<P>
The relatively poor quality of crops in some countries may also
trigger purchases of higher grades to meet milling needs.
</P>
<P>
In others, notably in India, the economic advantages of
importing wheat in deficit areas will lead to additional trade, IGC
said in its latest issue of Grain Market Report.
</P>
<P>
Global demand for feed wheat will depend on the availability
and pricing of lower quality grades, although significant amounts
have already been purchased from Ukraine and some Central and
Eastern European countries, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
