<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses Kuwait of Seizing its Ships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Tuesday accused Kuwait
of having seized three Iraqi dhows with their cargos last month,
the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
INA quoted an unnamed official source at the Iraqi ports as
saying that the Kuwaiti authorities detained the dhows named
al-Waleed, al-Tawfiq and al-Falah on July 17.
</P>
<P>
Al-Waleed was carrying 201 tons of millet, 102 tons of wool,
al-Tawfiq was carrying 793 tons of urea fertilizer and 12 tons of
plant seeds while al-Falah was carrying one ton of organic
fertilizer, said the source.
</P>
<P>
The source did not say whether these dhows had been released by
Kuwait or not.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Baghdad accused Kuwait of intercepting an
Indian ship carrying contracted items under the oil-for-food
program in Iraqi territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal with the United Nations, Iraq is
allowed to sell limited amount of oil in every six months to buy
food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies for its 24 million
people.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under the U.N. sanctions since it invaded Kuwait
in 1990, which touched off the 1991 Gulf War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
