<HEADLINE> Britain to Attract Tourists with Film Location Tours </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Britain is boosting film tourism
in a bid to attract movie buffs to the locations of box office
hits, the Reuters reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"From Shakespeare in Love" to "The Full Monty" and "Notting
Hill", fans are being enticed to relive the cinema moment by going
to the sites where the films were shot, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Films minister Janet Anderson is increasing the annual budget
from two million pounds (3.2 million U.S. dollars) to six million
pounds for regional tourist boards eager to promote "location
specials".
</P>
<P>
The country's Tourist Authority annually updates its "Movie Map
of Britain", which now lists more than 67 films and TV classics in
110 locations.
</P>
<P>
Osborne House in the Isle of Wight recorded a 25 percent
increase in tourist numbers after the filming of "Mrs Brown",
starring Dame Judi Dench.
</P>
<P>
Three Scottish-based films -- "Rob Roy", "Braveheart" and "Loch
Ness" -- are estimated to have attracted up to 15 million pounds
in extra revenue, the authority said. 
</P>
