<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Military Forces Need More Money: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- If the Netherlands wishes to
continue to be able to achieve its military-political ambitions,
and to make a meaningful contribution to the new developments
within NATO and the European Union (EU), more money will have to
be channeled to its Ministry of Defense, said a report published
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch government said it has asked a research agency in the
Netherlands, the Advisory Council on International Affairs, to
study recent developments in international security and to map out
the consequences of those developments for the Dutch defense
policy and armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The council said in the report that greater military
flexibility and mobility is needed as a NATO member country in
order to sustain the ability to make an effective contribution in
the changing international security situation.
</P>
<P>
"It is precisely the armed forces of the European NATO member
states which fall short in this respect. Moreover, the European
countries themselves increasingly need to be able to assure their
military responsibilities, because American participation in
today's crisis management operations -- in contrast to the common
defense of NATO territory -- cannot be taken for granted. The
European military capability must therefore be strengthened, and
this will inevitably have consequences for the defense budgets of
the European countries concerned," the Dutch government cited the
report in a news release as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that the huge budget can no longer be
found within the defense apparatus itself, and the long-term
budgets for defense spending will therefore have to be increased.
</P>
<P>
"Otherwise, the ability to deploy Dutch armed forces will fall
short of what is needed, and this in turn will impact on support
for the defense apparatus and the ability to recruit new military
personnel," the study said.
</P>
<P>
The close interrelationship between these elements means that
there is a danger of a vicious circle being created "with negative
consequences for the future ability of the Netherlands to continue
contributing to peace, security and the international rule of
law," the study said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
