<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ceasefire Accord Only First Step to Peace: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Emile Ilunga, a faction leader of
the rebel Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD) said here Tuesday
that signing of the peace agreement is the first step in the long
way to peace in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader, backed by Rwanda, told a press conference
after signing the agreement that "everybody hopes peace will
follow the signing of the agreement and everybody is happy with
this development."
</P>
<P>
He said that his delegation visited Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni and informed him of RCD's will to sign the agreement,
which has already been signed by six African countries involved in
the DRC war.
</P>
<P>
Ilunga appreciated Zambian government for its quick move to
send its Minister of State House Eric Silwamba to talk to them.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that of the 50 founding RCD members 41 is working
with his faction which is based in Goma.
</P>
<P>
Illunga said there is only one RCD and no two RCD groups,
dismissing as "fictitious" the Kisangani-based RCD group led by
Ernest Wamba Dia Wamba and backed by Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader said if his group is attacked it will not
remain defenseless, but added that his group will be committed to
implementing the ceasefire agreement even if it is attacked.
</P>
<P>
A total of 46 founding members of the RCD signed the ceasefire
 agreement, which were signed on July 10 in Lusaka by DRC and its
 supporters-- Zimbabwe, Namibia, Angola as well as rebels'
supporters -- Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
RCD and the Movement for the Liberation for Congo (MLC) did
not sign the agreement because of the disagreement within the RCD
over who would sign it on behalf The rebel group.
</P>
<P>
MLC signed the agreement on August 1.
</P>
<P>
To break the deadlock, Southern African Development Community
(SADC) proposed that all the founding members be allowed to sign
the Lusaka agreement.
</P>
<P>
In May Ilunga ousted Wamba and was named by his supporters as
new leader of RCD. After the wrangle broke out Wamba moved from
Goma to Kisangani and has been insisting that he is still the
leader of the rebel group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
