<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Power Rationing to Last 6 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Power rationing in Kenya may
last as long as six months as the reduced power generation has
been caused by the low water level in the country's three main
energy reservoirs due to the poor long rains between March and
June.
</P>
<P>
Just a week ago, the Kenyan government announced power
rationing plans across the country with effect from September 1.
</P>
<P>
Power rationing would last next March when the long rains
season is expected to start, which would improve the water levels
in the reservoirs to allow power generation to return to normal,
said Florence Obura, spokeswoman of the Kenya Power and Lighting
Company (KPLC), here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Engineers from the Kenya Power Company said that water levels
of the main energy reservoirs are at the lowest since the
mid-1960's.
</P>
<P>
Power output in Kenya was under pressure because of a failure
to develop new generation capacity in the late 1980's and early
1990's, the KPLC official said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has liberalized the power sector and encouraged
independent power producers to build power plants. So far only two
power plants constructed by independent power producers are
operational, which account for a small portion of national power
production.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Power Company said that the country's current peak
power demand stands at 760 megawatts against available capacity of
676.5 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
However, KPLC has assured that essential services and
installations would not suffer from the rationing. They include
hospitals, schools, military sites and vital industries like oil
refineries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Stock Exchange Hits Lowest Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 31 (Xinhua) - Kenya's stock market plunged to
its lowest level in nearly six years on Tuesday due to the
falling profits in the key agricultural sector and the
government's inability to revive its economy.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said the Nairobi Stock Exchange's main 20-share
index dropped 63.79 points or 2.49 percent to close at 2,493.50
points, the lowest since December 14, 1993.  The stock
exchange market has been in trouble since the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) suspended a loan of 205 million U.S. dollars
to Kenya in July 1997 because of rampant corruption among
government officials and poor governance, according to analysts
here.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, the government has taken
various measures, including the frequent changes of senior
government officials, to revive its economy, but there is still
no sign for the recovery. Corporate profits are weak and the
country's infrastructure is improved slowly .
</P>
<P>
Its economic growth has dropped from 4.6 percent in 1996 to
just 1.8 percent in 1998 and this year is expected to be no
better than the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
