<HEADLINE> Tanzania Looks for Partners to Fund Rural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 31 (Xinhua) - Tanzania is looking forward
to establishing a special fund for rural electrification, the
Deputy Minister of Energy and Minerals Manju Msambya said here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Opening the second national seminar on rural power cooperatives
Msambya requested donors to contribute to the creation and funding
of the facility which will greatly assist Tanzania in realizing
rural electrification.
</P>
<P>
He also called on private businessmen to invest in the sector.
</P>
<P>
Msambya said that the Tanzanian government is looking for a new
energy policy aimed to encourage more private participation in the
power sector as a way of accelerating electrification in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Charcoal is still the major source of energy in most Tanzanian
households, accounting for about 90 percent of the total primary
energy use, the deputy minister said.
</P>
<P>
The managing director of Tanzania Electric Supply Company
Limited (TANESCO), Baruany Luhanga, said at the opening of the
seminar that achieving rural electrification by different
cooperatives has been proven successful in the United States,
Sweden and other developed countries.
</P>
<P>
However, he expressed his concern about the high electricity
tariff in rural areas and called for affordable services to rural
power consumers. 
</P>
