<HEADLINE> Russian Envoy Returns to NATO Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Russia's envoy to NATO, Colonel-
General Viktor Zavarzin, has resumed his duties at NATO
headquarters in Brussels, the Interfax news agency reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zavarzin was recalled to Moscow in protest against NATO air-
strikes over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
However, his return does not indicate that Russia has widened
its cooperation with the military alliance from peacekeeping to
full scale operations, Interfax said, quoting Russian military
officials.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Russia-NATO Permanent Joint Military Council,
which is to resume functions in Brussels next Monday, will focus
on the peacekeeping operation in Kosovo, before it resumes work at
the ambassadorial level on September 15.
</P>
<P>
Zavarzin is expected to deal with "all the negative aspects"
of the Russian peacekeepers' part in this operation, which can
only be done within the framework of a normal negotiating process.
Interfax quoted Russian military sources in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Zavarzin was promoted to the rank of colonel-general after
Russian troops made a surprise march to Pristina, capital of the
Yugoslav province, ahead of NATO troops in early June.
</P>
<P>
Russia has some 3,600 troops in Kosovo as part of a NATO-led
peacekeeping force of about 40,000.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Russian Foreign Ministry issued
a statement Wednesday urging the peacekeepers, including both
military and civilian personnel, to be objective in their
operations rather than exercising personal likes or dislikes of
ethnic groups living in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
It condemned the month-long cover-up of the discovery of a
mass grave containing 15 ethnic Serbs killed in Gnjlane, which is
inside the U.S. sector of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also expressed its indignation over the slow
progress of the disarming of Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
"Albanian armed formations should have sharply curtailed their
activities, but no noticeable sign of this exists," the statement
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
