<HEADLINE> Pyongyang Denies Possibility of Future Talks with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Pyongyang denied any
possibility for future general-level talks with the United States,
after the two sides failed again to reach any agreement on
demarcating a maritime boundary on the sea off western Korea, the
Korean Central News Agency (KCNA) said.
</P>
<P>
General Ri Chan Bok was the chief negotiator of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), while Major General Michael
Dunn represented the U.S.
</P>
<P>
During the talks at the truce village of Panmunjom on Wednesday,
the DPRK repeated its stance that Pyongyang has never recognized
the so-called northern Limit Line, which was unilaterally set up
by the U.S. at the end of the Korean War in 1953.The DPRK
spokesman said the U.S. lacked the necessary sincerity in solving
the boundary dispute between the north and the south.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, DPRK has no choice but to withdraw from the
meaningless game of marathon talks and to do whatever is possible
to protect the integrity of its maritime territory, KCNA said.
</P>
<P>
This was the 6th round of general-level talks since the naval
forces from the Republic of Korea (ROK) and DPRK exchanged gun
fire off the Korean Peninsula's west coast on June 15 this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
