<HEADLINE> Jordan Announces Partial Cabinet Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul
Raouf Rawabdeh Wednesday announced a partial reshuffle to his
23-member cabinet, including the appointment of two new ministers
and the shifting of three other portfolios.
</P>
<P>
Saeed Shuqum, a fomer member of Jordan's national basketball
team and acting president of the Jordanian basketball
association, was sworn in as Minister of Youth and Sports to
replace Mohammed Kheir Mamsar, Jordan's official news agency
Petra said.
</P>
<P>
Mamsar resigned on July 3 after failing to disuade Kuwait from
boycotting the ninth Pan-Arab games in Amman due to the
participation of Iraq whose 1990 invasion of Kuwait led to the
1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Mamsar's resignation triggered Wednesday's cabinet reshuffle,
the first since Rawabdeh took office on March 4.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Jumaa Wahsh was appointed Minister of Social
Development to replace Faisal Rufoo, who received the cultural
portfolio, Petra said.
</P>
<P>
In the most noticeable change, the portfolio of information
was given to Deputy Prime Minister Aymen Majali to replace Nasser
Lawzi who was shifted to head the Ministry of Transport.
</P>
<P>
Lawzi is known as a liberal politician who called for greater
press freedom and had been at odds with Rawabdeh, who preferred a
more conservative policy on information.
</P>
<P>
Former Transport Minister Jamal Sarayreh remained in the
cabinet with his other portfolios - Minister of Post and
Telecommunications. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
