<HEADLINE> Canada Cancels Trade Mission to Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Canada has canceled a high-
profile trade mission to Australia, the Globe and Mail newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien
decided Tuesday to "defer" the trade mission because of the
absence of many provincial premiers.
</P>
<P>
Chretien is scheduled to leave next week for the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) meeting in New Zealand. He will then
travel to Japan to head a delegation of about 200 businessmen and
some provincial premiers, who do not want to extend the trip
beyond Japan, the newspaper added.
</P>
<P>
About 150 Canadian businessmen signed up for the Australian
portion of the "Team Canada" mission, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Australian High Commissioner Gregory Wood was quoted as saying
that he is disappointed at the change in the mission, but his
government understands the vagaries of political scheduling.
</P>
<P>
In a news release Tuesday, Chretien said all of the provincial
premiers had initially agreed to go to Australia, but several
dropped out because of elections, scheduling conflicts and
personal reasons, according to the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
