<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Unveils New Financial Products for Borrowers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Launched
Wednesday new loan and hedging products for its borrowers,
offering developing countries more flexibility in managing their
financial risks.
</P>
<P>
"Today's unveiling of fixed-spread LIBOR-based loans and
hedging products comes in response to demand from the bank's
borrowing countries for more flexible financial products and
risk-management tools," the World Bank said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The fixed-spread loan will be available for loans for which the
invitation to negotiate will be issued on or after September 1,
1999. It will offer World Bank borrowers unprecedented flexibility
to tailor their loan repayment terms to suit their project or loan
portfolio needs.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, it will give borrowers the option to change
the currency, or fix, cap, or collar the interest rate of their
loan at any time prior to loan's financial maturity.
</P>
<P>
The hedging products would enable borrowers to enter into
currency and interest rate swaps with the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The bank will also be ready to sell borrowers interest rate
caps and collars to assist them in lowering their interest rate
risk, or enter with them into commodity swaps, with the latter on
a pilot basis initially. Borrowers transacting hedges with the
bank would beed to do so under a master derivatives agreement to
be signed with the bank.
</P>
<P>
"These products and the outreach which accompanies them should
have a major development impact. Over time, they will increase
borrowers' financial market skills and help them manage other
balance sheet risks," said Graeme Wheeler, director of the bank's
Financial Products and Services Department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libyans Mark 30th Anniversary of Revolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TRIPOLI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Celebrations for the 30th
anniversary of Libya's 1969 Revolution kicked off Wednesday with a
mass parade at Zawiyah city.
</P>
<P>
Zawiyah, a small city 40 kilometers west of the capital Tripoli,
is practically unknown to people outside Libya. But it drew the
attention of media Wednesday by its Alfateh Zawiyah Wedding, an
event held to mark the revolution.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of local residents emptied the city, which
has a population of about half a million, by gathering at a
downtown square to celebrate what they described as a "special
holiday."
</P>
<P>
Shops, bazaars and schools are closed for the event. Buildings
along the city's four-kilometer-long Public Street are decorated
with colorful flags. Posters featuring Libyan leader Muammar
Ghaddafi are everywhere to be seen.
</P>
<P>
People holding national flags and portraits of Ghaddafi marched
through the street, chanting "Alfateh" "Alfateh," meaning
"victory" of Libyan Revolution.
</P>
<P>
"I am very happy today. You know 30 years ago, our leader freed
the Libyan people from the monarchy," said a female professor from
the Zawiyah University, who join the local residents in the
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
On September 1, 1969, a group of young officers led by Ghaddafi
overthrew the monarchy in a military coup. They established a
Revolutionary Command Council with Ghaddafi as chairman and
proclaimed the Libyan Arab Republic.
</P>
<P>
The country was renamed the Great Socialist People's Libyan
Arab Jamahiriya in October 1986.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats from some African and Arab countries were also
present at the gathering besides international journalists invited
for the occation.
</P>
<P>
The national celebrations, the first since the United Nations
Security Council suspended on April 5 its sanctions against Libya,
will last for days. A grand parade is expected to be held in
Tripoli with participation of troops from 12 African nations.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. suspended the sanctions on Libya which were in place
since 1992, after Ghaddafi agreed to hand over the two Libyans
suspected of bombing a Pan Am jetliner over Lockerbie, Scotland in
1988 which killed 270 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
