<HEADLINE> Britain Pledges to Help Restore Power Supply in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, Sept 1 (Xinhua) - Britain said on Wednesday it would
pledge an extra 700,000 pounds ( about 1.13 million U.S. dollars)
to ensure that war-shattered Kosovo has reliable power supplies.
</P>
<P>
"This is continuing proof of the UK government's commitment to
rebuilding Kosovo, especially as the cold weather season
approaches," Trade Minister Richard Caborn said.
</P>
<P>
Caborn, who is scheduled to visit Kosovo next month, said the
consortium was also looking to the longer term, developing
proposals for future power generation, transmission and
distribution.
</P>
<P>
"With the help of the UK government money, it is estimated that
within one to two years British companies have prospects of
gaining contracts worth between 10 million and 20 million pounds,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"This will be from work arising out of the concession directly
related to the rehabilitation of the power stations, substations
and transmission lines," he said.
</P>
<P>
Britain played a very hawkish role in NATO's 72-day-long air
strikes against Yugoslavia, which seriously damaged the Balkan
country and killing thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
Most of the power plants in Kosovo were also seriously damaged
during the air strikes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
