<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Culture Week to Open With Boom in Paris (Part I) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Under the warm autumn Paris
sunshine, a festive Chinese atmosphere was being prepared by the
Maison de UNESCO, which is located south of the Eiffel Tower, for
the official opening of "China Culture Week -'99 Paris,"
beginning in the evening of September 1.
</P>
<P>
Red banners heralding the festival were hanging on light posts
surrounding the building at the south end of the elegant Place de
Fontenoy, just opposite the 18th century Ecole Militaire, with its
imposing imperial architecture, where Napoleon once reviewed his
army.
</P>
<P>
A giant Chinese lion wearing a red costume sits at the garden
of the Maison de UNESCO, greeting the long line of cars of
Parisians returning from two months of summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
Inside the building, Much of China's history has been
recreated. A miniature Peking Opera stage has been constructed in
the center of the great exhibition hall, complete with a wide
range of classic figures from ancient Chinese dramas, including a
heroic woman fighting Mongolian invaders, and another heroic woman
who seeks to avenge her husband who was wrongly executed because
of the treachery of his friends.
</P>
<P>
You can also hear traditional folk songs from the Loess
plateau in northwest Shaanxi Province, or watch a craftswoman
demonstrate how to clip popular Chinese paper crafts with scissors.
</P>
<P>
Through the half-veiled glass wall of a separate room in the
corner of the hall, you can see one of the China's most precious
ancient treasures -- the 2,400 year-old chime bells of the Chu
Kingdom from the Spring and Autumn Warring Kingdoms period. The
bells were found in Suixian, Hubei province.
</P>
<P>
 Ma Chengyuan, president of the Shanghai Museum, and an expert
in paleography and bronzes of the Shang and Zhou dynasties, said:
"Ancient Chinese bronzes belong to the world and do not have
frontiers; the French people are among the few who really
understand them."
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac is also an expert on ancient
Chinese bronzes, said Ma, who was invited by Chirac to dinner at
the Elysee Presidential Palace after his arrival in Paris this
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Rebel Leader Rejects Egyptian-Libyan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Southern Sudanese rebel leader
John Garang on Wednesday rejected the Egyptian-Libyan plan aimed
at helping put an end to his country's civil war.
</P>
<P>
Garang said in a statement that his Sudan People's Liberation
Army (SPLA) sought peace through the negotiations with the
Sudanese government conducted in Nairobi, Kenya under the auspices
of the Inter-Governmental Authority on Development, or IGAD.
</P>
<P>
"The SPLA remains committed to the IGAD peace initiative as the
most credible and viable meditation mechanism, and furthermore
considers that there should not be two parallel initiatives,"
Garang said.
</P>
<P>
Through the Egyptian-Libyan plan, the Khartoum government had
an opportunity for its "reckless practice of forum shopping," he
argued.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Libya proposed early last month the plan, which calls
for a permanent cease-fire in Sudan and a national reconciliation
conference. The plan has been accepted by the government and the
National Democratic Alliance (NDA), a coalition of northern
opposition parties and the SPLA.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA "urges that the IGAD peace initiative and the
Libya-Egyptian initiative should be coordinated by the two sets of
mediators to avoid parallelism," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA has met intermittently with government negotiators in
Nairobi under the auspices of IGAD, but the talks have never
produced more than agreements on short-term cease-fires.
</P>
<P>
The government has opposed the participation of the NDA in the
talks hosted by IGAD, which comprises representatives of Kenya,
Uganda, Ethiopia, Eritrea, Sudan, Somalia and Djibouti.
</P>
<P>
Garang arrived in Cairo on Monday and met with former Sudanese
Prime Minister Sadiq al-Mahdi and other members of his Umma party,
who form a major element of the NDA coalition. He also met with
Egypt's Deputy Prime Minister Youssef Wali who handles relations
with Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 2 million people have died in Sudan's civil war and
ensuing famines since 1983. The SPLA draws its support from the
Christians and animists of the south who seek autonomy from the
Islamic north. 
</P>
</TEXT>
