<HEADLINE> Sensex Prices Fall Further At Bombay Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Decision by the Bombay Stock
Exchange (BSE) to impose additional carryforward margins sent the
market reeling under pressure Wednesday with the sensitive index
(SENSEX) plunging by nearly 74 points owing to all-round bull
liquidation.
</P>
<P>
Speculators sold heavily to reduce their outstanding positions
following BSE's measures to curb excessive volatility.
</P>
<P>
In order to check the recent volatility, BSE imposed additional
carryforward margins and also reduced the intra and inter
settlement scripwise limits effective from next week.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark BSE sensitive index opened slightly up at
4,910.64 points and gradually moved downwards to a day's low of
4,813.21 before closing at 4,824.44 as against Tuesday's close of
4,898.21, showing a sharp loss of 73.77 points, or 1.51 percent.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-100 index also dropped by 39.70 points to 2,153.24
compared with the previous close of 2,192.24.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the net outstanding positions of nearly 25 billion
rupees at the end of Tuesday seemed to be much higher and some
correction was imminent for a healthy market.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-200 and the Dollex were quoted substantially down at
494.85 and 189.53 points as against last close of 503.45 and
192.78 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-500 index also went down 24.44 points to 1,461.38 from
the previous close of 1,485.82. 
</P>
