<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Culture Week to Open in Paris (Part3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In his message of congratulations, Chinese President Jiang
Zemin said that the China Culture Week is significant in
promoting friendship between French and Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's French counterpart, President Chirac, said the
principal theme of the culture week -- China Marches Toward the
21st Century -- shows that the "great country, rich in a
tradition of several millenniums, is prepared to whole-heartedly
enter the modern age."
</P>
<P>
The Secretary General of UNESCO, Frederico Mayor, said that
through this cultural week, his organization wants to let the
public see a true picture of Chinese culture, which is often
presented in a twisted way and misunderstood in the West.
</P>
<P>
In the French popular culture, China is viewed as a mysterious
country which has two Homeric monuments -- the Forbidden City and
the Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
To let the French general public get closer to China, an extra
program, "Intervilles" (intercity), a sports competition program,
will be presented by France's number one television channel TF1
and the Chinese China Central TV during the cultural week.
</P>
<P>
The famous French TV actor Jean-Pierre Foucault, who will
participate in the competition between teams from Paris and
Beijing on Saturday night, said that for him, China is a vast
country with great cooking.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, I can't wait for the competition, because it is
clothed in an exceptional character," said Foucault when
commenting on the first international version of "Intervilles"
since its creation by French television in 1962.
</P>
<P>
The mayor of Paris, Jean Tiberi, will head the Paris team.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing team also intends to enter its best in the
competition.
</P>
<P>
The competition will be held in front of the famous Chateau de
Vincennes military fortification in southwest Paris. Five
thousand spectators and hundreds of thousands of television
viewers will watch the show, which will be broadcast live by TF1
and CCTV.
</P>
<P>
The French sports star Nathalie Simon, who will also join the
program, said she was amused that CCTV has provided twin girls,
Fang Fang and Yuan Yuan, both 19 years old, to play her part in
the Chinese version of "Intervilles" in China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese version of the Interville show has won great
success after one year of broadcasting by CCTV, said Xin Shaoying,
the co-producer of the show who studied television production in
France.
</P>
<P>
This time, the twin girls will help Nathalie serve as the
hostess of the show in French and Chinese.
</P>
<P>
One segment of the show will feature a French cow or bull
chasing French and Chinese runners in a circle filled with wooden
barriers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nathan Sworn in as Singapore's Sixth President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 1 (Xinhua) -- S.R. Nathan, a career public
officer and veteran diplomat, was sworn into office Wednesday
evening as Singapore's sixth president at a ceremony at the
presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
At the swearing-in ceremony attended by cabinet members, MPs,
personalities of communities and representatives from all walks of
life, the new president reviewed a guard of honor and delivered a
speech.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong made a welcoming speech
before Nathan.
</P>
<P>
Goh said, "The president is the head of state and the symbol of
the nation" and he reiterated that "this role is ceremonial."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also said the president's functions are not
ceremonial when he exercises custodial powers to decide whether to
allow the government to draw upon hard-earned past reserves and
whether to accept or reject nominations to key appointments.
</P>
<P>
"As goal-keeper, the president becomes our last line of
defense," Goh said. "If he fumbles, Singapore may never recover
from an irresponsible or dishonest government."
</P>
<P>
Goh repeated what he had said six year ago to then president
Ong Teng Cheong, saying "my government has no intention of
squandering the financial reserves we have so painstakingly
accumulated, nor depart from the cardinal principle of appointing
the best officers to key positions on merit."
</P>
<P>
"In short, my government will not give you cause to exercise
your veto powers," Goh said.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, President Nathan vowed to be a president for all
Singaporeans, saying "every community of Singaporeans will be my
parish."
</P>
<P>
He promised "to give of my best, the very best I can, and
without fear or favor."
</P>
<P>
He also pledged to exercise the president's custodial powers
"in Singapore's national interests, as my duty and conscience
requires."
</P>
<P>
Returned unopposed on nomination day for the presidential
elections, Nathan assumes presidency without a national polling
and succeeds Ong Teng Cheong as Singapore's second elected
president.
</P>
<P>
Before the swearing-in ceremony, a farewell ceremony was held
for Singapore's fifth president Ong Teng Cheong who ended his
six-year term Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
