<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Negotiator Urges Israel to Refrain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 1 (Xinhua) - Following his meeting with
Israeli officials, Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb Erekat
Wednesday urged Israel to refrain from issuing ultimatum and
threats.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Jerusalem, Erekat said that he and
his Israeli counterpart, Prime Minister Ehud Barak's envoy Gilad
Sher, have made maximum efforts to bridge the differences between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said the two remaining blocks in the negotiations are
the issues concerning release of Palestinian prisoners and
resumption of the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said that he has submitted new suggestions to the
Israeli negotiators on bridging the differences, and hoped to
continue the talks.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Palestinian National Authority has
shown determination to reach peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
"I would urge my colleagues and the Israeli government to
refrain from ultinatum or threats," Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued earlier in the day, Sher said that from
the Israeli respective, the negotiation with the Palestinians is
over.
</P>
<P>
He also said that no further meeting is planned between
him and Erekat.
</P>
<P>
Sher also warned that Barak may announce in his cabinet
meeting later on Wednesday that the Palestinians are interested in
the implementation of the "original" Wye agreement, which means
it will be carried out according to Israeli interpretation.
</P>
<P>
Barak has threatened that if no agreement is reached on
Wednesday evening, Israel will take unilateral actions.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians have been engaged in intensified
efforts to reach an agreement on Israeli proposals over the
modification of the Wye interim agreement before United States
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright starts a visit to the
region on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The main issue blocking a breakthrough is the release of
Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians demand that Israel release 650 political
prisoners, those jailed for anti-Israel activities, but Israel
insists that it will release only 500 prisoners and will not
free those Palestinians involved in killings of Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Barak has proposed to postpone the last of the
three stages of troop withdrawals stipulated in the Wye accord
until February next year, when the two sides are supposed to
have worked out a framework for the final-status talks, which
deal with thorny issues like Jerusalem and Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinians want Israel to complete all the troop
withdrawals at an earlier date in line with the original
timetable of the Wye accord, which calls on Israel to hand
over 13 percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians in
three stages over a period of 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
Barak's hard-line predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu carried out
the first stage of the agreement late last year before
freezing it in a failed attempt to woo back rebellious
coalition partners opposed to territorial concession to the
Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New River Transport Hub Project Completed in SW China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A major river transport
project in southwest China has entered a new stage today with the
completion of its hydro-power plant.
</P>
<P>
The project, which has taken five years to construct, has cost
2.08 billion yuan including a World Bank loan of 80 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
It is located in Guigang, in southwestern Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region, and on the Xijiang River, the main stream of
the country's third largest river, the Pearl River.
</P>
<P>
The hub is composed of a transport center, a hydraulic power
plant and a cargo operations station. It has also included the
dredging of the river course from Guigang to Nanning, the regional
capital.
</P>
<P>
The project will assist river transport, flood prevention and
irrigation. Its power plant has four generators and a total
capacity of 120,000 kw.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Delegation to Leave for U.N. Human Rights Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Secretary for Home Affairs
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) David Lan
will lead a delegation to a United Nations hearing on HKSAR's
human rights report under the International Covenant on Civil and
Political Rights (ICCPR) in Geneva on October 29 and November 1.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a function at the Lingnan University Wednesday, Lan
said the delegation, comprising representatives of relevant
government bureaus and departments, will answer openly the
questions put to them by members of the U.N. Human Rights
Committee, which is the treaty monitoring body of the ICCPR.
</P>
<P>
"During the hearing, I will brief the committee on the human
rights development in the HKSAR after its reunification with the
mainland," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lan urged the university students to read the human rights
report as it will deepen their understanding of public affairs in
Hong Kong and the government's efforts to uphold the freedoms and
rights the people here have long enjoyed and cherished.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Hong Kong is a free and vibrant society that
treasures and tolerates divergent viewpoints, Lan also urged the
students to play an active role in community affairs and not to
hesitate to express their views.
</P>
<P>
Lan also revealed that he had sent an invitation to the
chairperson of the treaty monitoring body for a visit to Hong Kong
before the hearing so that the chairperson and her delegation
could see for themselves the actual situation in Hong Kong and
talk directly to different sectors of the community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
