<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Stock Exchange,
one of the two bourses in China, today named its Top 50 listed
companies based on their income from main business activities, net
profits, assets and market value.
</P>
<P>
The Top 50 were selected by "Listed Companies," a magazine
operated by the East China Branch of the "People's Daily", the
country's leading newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Tu Shaoguang, general manager of the Shanghai bourse, said that
the selection of the Top 50 is of profound importance and
demonstrates the achievements of China's ongoing economic reform
and the restructuring of the state sector.
</P>
<P>
"Stock markets in China are designed to help reinvigorate state
companies and to turn them into blue chip outfits as well as being
an economic pillar of the nation," Tu said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to note that most of the Top 500 world companies
listed every year by "Fortune" magazine of the United States are
public firms.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai will host the Fortune Forum '99 later this month, a
widely publicized event which is attracting the CEOs and key
officials from a wide range of world-beating companies to discuss,
amongst other topics, China's role in the 21st Century. 
