<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Mowlam Urges Parties to Back Northern Irish Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Northern Ireland
Secretary Mo Mowlam on Wednesday urged parties from both sides of
the community not to give up on the Good Friday Agreement.
</P>
<P>
The basic desire to end the conflict was still there, she said.
"That is why the parties should be in there, talking to each other
about the Mitchell review, not walking away."
</P>
<P>
"People know the Good Friday Agreement is the best chance we
have. But unless there is confidence throughout the community it
simply won't work," she told an audience at Ulidia Integrated
school in Carrickfergus in County Antrim.
</P>
<P>
Former U.S. Senator George Mitchell is to begin a major review
of the Good Friday Agreement next week, amid growing fears about
the future of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam's speech was widely considered as a major pitch to both
the Ulster Unionists and Sinn Fein to give that review a chance to
succeed. Her speech comes at a time when there is growing anger
among unionists about recent violence that has been blamed on the
IRA, and unease within the catholic community over a spate of
loyalist attacks.
</P>
<P>
The secretary of state said the murder of Charles Bennett and
an alleged republican gun-running plot from the United States, as
well as the continuing loyalist violence, had raised genuine
concerns over the state of the paramilitary cease-fire; but people
had to ask themselves how far Northern Ireland had come in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
She then praised the bravery of the parties supporting the
agreement, noting their efforts were taking Northern Ireland
forward to the future, not back to the past.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam said her ruling on the cease-fire had "not been about
appeasement, not about turning a blind eye, but about attempting
to help this province end its historic conflict."
</P>
<P>
Turning to the recent threats made against teenagers in
Northern Ireland by paramilitary groups, Mowlam said: "Let no one
be in any doubt, I condemn kangaroo courts of any kind."
</P>
<P>
Mowlam's remarks come at a time when neither the Ulster
Unionists or Sinn Fein have yet decided whether to participate in
the crucial review of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Ulster Unionists responded furiously when Mowlam announced
last week that she believed the IRA cease-fire was still intact --
despite reports of recent violence and alleged gun-running -- and
have postponed a decision on a possible boycott of the Agreement
review. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
