<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Rebel leaders who took up arms 13 months ago to topple
Congolese President Laurent Kabila signed a cease-fire plan
Tuesday aimed at ending a civil war that has drawn five
neighboring African countries into battle.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. State Secretary Madeleine K. Albright departs Wednesday
on her first visit to the Middle East since the election of Israel
's new prime minister, Ehud Barak, rekindled hopes for a final
peace settlement between Israel and the Palestinians, Syria and
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The Clinton administration, pressed by investigations into
money laundering and capital flight out of Russia, is being forced
anew to justify its policies of bold economic assistance to Moscow
during the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
-- Anti-independence thugs who have terrorized East Timor for
months reasserted themselves Tuesday, one day after an
extraordinarily peaceful referendum on the region's future in
which, officials said, 98.6 percent of eligible voters cast their
ballots.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The first indicators gauging the U.S. economy's strength in
August released Tuesday showed no sign of a slowdown, as
manufacturing activity accelerated and consumer optimism remained
high.
</P>
<P>
-- Intel Corp. is unveiling a new processor that can replace
the custom chips in Internet-networking gear, part of its drive to
be a big supplier to the communications industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
