<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agricultural Land Excluded From Philippine Charter Change: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Agricultural lands are excluded
from the proposed 1987 Philippine Constitution amendment aimed to
allow foreigners to own land in the nation, a senior government
official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu made the statement when
presenting his department's budget before the members of a House
subcommittee, Philippine News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Agricultural lands are excluded in the land ownership issue,"
Espiritu told the House members.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the economic constitutional changes being
pushed by President Joseph Estrada are for the charter to
stipulate a general economic policy which would be effective only
after Congress shall have enacted an enabling law on land
ownership, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
"The 1987 charter would only open opportunities. It is still
Congress which will have to set the limitations. So, there is no
danger that national interest will be prejudiced," Espiritu said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Espiritu explained that land ownership does not mean
productivity. "We need capital to make them productive," he said.
</P>
<P>
"By allowing foreigners to own non-agricultural lands would
open many options for increased inflow of the needed capital to
develop our local industries," he explained.
</P>
<P>
"We need capital to ensure productive human and natural
resources," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
