<HEADLINE> Thailand to Raise Growth Target: Finance Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will raise
its growth rate target of one percent following the central bank's
optimistic projection, Thai Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanahaeminda said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that his ministry is working for a new growth target of
over one percent after the Bank of Thailand (BOT) forecast Tuesday
that the Thai economy can grow by three to four percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin was quoted by Thailand News Agency as saying that the
new growth target will be announced after the Office of the
National Economic and Social Development Board releases its
economic report for the second quarter, expected by the end of
this month.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin noted that increase in domestic production and
consumption as well as exports were the main reasons for the
economic revival of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The BOT forecast that the Thai economy could grow by three to
four percent this year due to the signs of economic recovery such
as a 6.6 percent year-on-year export increase in July and rising
industrial index and domestic consumption.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's manufacturing output in July was up 13.7 percent
compared to the same period last year while surplus in current and
trade accounts soared to 1.2 billion and 976 million U.S. dollars
respectively due to rising tourism revenue and slower pace of
import growth, the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
The BOT's projection is in line with that of the Finance
Ministry's Fiscal Policy Office, which says that most economic
indicators of the Thai economy have moved upwards since May,
including industrial index, domestic consumption and exports with
a moderate inflation rate of 0.5 to one percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
