<HEADLINE> U.N. Rapporteur Arrives in Pakistan for Women Rights Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Special United Nations
rapporteur for violence against women Swami Radhika arrived here
Wednesday on a two-week visit to Pakistan and Afghanistan for
talks on women rights.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. rapporteur will proceed to Afghanistan next week to
analyze the situation arising from violence against women in the
country, especially woman refugees, said U.N. Information Center
spokesman Stephanie Bunker here.
</P>
<P>
Swami, a lawyer by profession, will meet U.N. officials and
representatives of NGOs in Afghanistan and discuss with them
matters relating to violence against women, according to Bunker.
</P>
<P>
U.N. sources said Afghanistan's ruling Taliban have agreed to
allow Swami's visit and promised to facilitate her during her
stay.
</P>
<P>
Taliban, which closed down education for women, have been under
fierce criticism for their women rights record.
</P>
<P>
Swami will also evaluate the situation of women rights in
Pakistan. A recent report said that in every second a Pakistani
woman is the victim of direct or indirect form of mental or
physical violence against them including rape, murder, chopping of
limbs or being burnt alive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
