<HEADLINE> Beijing-Based Steel Maker Marks Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Shougang Iron and Steel
Complex, a well-known steel maker based in the Chinese capital,
celebrated the 80th anniversary of its founding today but with a
warning that it has to diversify to survive.
</P>
<P>
President of the Shougang group Bi Qun urged staff to work
harder to develop hi-tech products and explore international
markets.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that the plant will no longer increase the
production of iron and steel products and by next year the complex
will have to earn 50 percent of its profits from non-steel or
overseas businesses.
</P>
<P>
The Shougang is one of the largest steel makers in China.
Between 1979-1998, the company handed over 25.6 billion yuan as
profits and taxes to the state revenue, while it also kept 16.98
billion yuan for its own use, mainly for technological renovation
and expansion of steel production.
</P>
<P>
Since 1979, the company has carried out a series of reforms and
has become a multinational firm engaged in a dozen different
industries.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the group, with a total staff of 210,000 produced 7.51
million tons of iron, 8.02 million tons of steel and 7.03 million
tons of steel plate, 3.1 times, 4.5 times and six times the
figures of twenty years before.
</P>
<P>
Last year, it generated 942 million yuan in profits and 2.16
billion yuan in pre-tax profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
