<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's GDP Growth May Turn Negative: Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) growth, estimated at 2.5 percent for 1998, is
forecast to slow this year and could even turn negative in the
final months of the year, a local financial institution said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Standard Chartered Bank said in its Business Trends in Zimbabwe
that output would fall in all three productive sectors of
agriculture, mining and manufacturing, so that the minimal growth
forecast would come from the services sector.
</P>
<P>
This is in line with a recent forecast by the Reserve Bank of
Zimbabwe which projected that growth in real GDP for 1999 was only
1.1 percent due to the poor performance of the mining and
manufacturing sectors.
</P>
<P>
Standard Chartered Bank said in 1980, agriculture, mining and
manufacturing accounted for 48 percent of GDP but currently their
share had fallen below 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
During 1990s, real GDP growth was estimated to have grown 2.2
percent annually, while population growth had averaged 3.1 percent
a year.
</P>
<P>
The bank said as a result, GDP per head had fallen about eight
percent over the period.
</P>
<P>
With per capita incomes certain to decline again in 1999, the
probability was that Zimbabwe would start the new millennium with
per capita incomes no higher than at independence in 1980, it
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 8 Killed in Fresh Communal Clashes in Ambon, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- At least eight people died and
six others were injured in two fresh communal clashes in Maluku,
Indonesia, on Wednesday, according to the Antara News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The clashes occurred in Baguala subdistrict in the provincial
capital of Ambon and Saparua subdistrict in Central Maluku.
</P>
<P>
The deaths had not been caused by security forces' actions but
by the rioters involved who fought each other with knives and
self-made bombs, Ambon police chief Lt. Col. Ghufron said.
</P>
<P>
He said security forces succeeded in quelling the conflicts
within two hours with the help of military personnel.
</P>
<P>
The police were investigating the clashes but had so far not
made any arrests, Ghufron said.
</P>
<P>
The clashes in Ambon first broke out in January, in which more
than a hundred people were killed and tens of thousands of people
were forced to flee their villages.
</P>
<P>
Local religious figures, along with the military, have tried to
reconcile the warring camps but clashes broke out again in
mid-July.
</P>
<P>
Ambon police spokesman M.J. Yohanis said since July 24, a total
of 132 civilians had been killed and 458 others injured in
communal clashes in the region.
</P>
<P>
In addition, one security officer died and 38 others were
injured.
</P>
<P>
Yohanis said the clashes had also destroyed 765 houses, 196
shops, one bank, three hotels, six government offices and eight
commercial buildings, seven houses of worship, two school
buildings and 19 cars.
</P>
<P>
The police seized 77 people (18 of whom were detained as
suspects) and confiscated 276 weapons, including self-made bombs
and bullets, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
