<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Black Buck on Decline in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The population of black
bucks inhabiting in Nepal is on decline for lack of well-planned
and concerted efforts and there is an urgent need for the
protection of the animal, the official RSS news agency reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
belonging to the antelope family, the black buck is one of the
endangered species of wildlife in the world and is among the 26
protected species in Nepal. The number of the animal in Nepal
reached its high of 177 in 1984 and began the downslide
afterwards. It declined to just 54 in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
The black buck, which inhabits in the Bardiya district in
southwestern Nepal, prefers to live in dry grassland and in close
proximity to human settlements. Large numbers of black bucks are
said to have escaped to neighboring India when they are driven
away by local farmers as these animals cause great damages to
their crops.
</P>
<P>
Once in the Indian territory, the animals are pursued further
by Indian farmers, thus giving them no chances to return.
</P>
<P>
Lack of effective management, scarcity of fodder and water
around its natural habitat and the gradual depletion of pasture
and forage due to overgrazing by domestic animals are the main
reasons for the dwindling of black buck population.
</P>
<P>
The black buck is so agile that it can jump up to 10-15 feet
above the ground and run 80 kilometers per hour. It is also known
for its special ability to make three turns during a leap in the
air. 
</P>
</TEXT>
