<HEADLINE> 2 Philippine Oil Companies Charged With Tax Evasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Bureau of
Internal Revenue (BIR) has filed a tax evasion case against
Petrolink Corporation and is filing a similar suit versus Lubwell
Corp., a presidential source said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a press briefing, presidential spokesman Jerry Barrican said
the case against Petrolink was filed on August 23 while the case
against Lubwell will be lodged within this week.
</P>
<P>
Barrican added that six other oil companies were sent pre-audit
notices in compliance with the principle of due process.
</P>
<P>
"Appropriate charges will be filed against them later on should
evidence so warrant," he said.
</P>
<P>
BIR Commissioner Beethoven Rualo earlier reported that these
oil companies have declared their sales of jet fuel as kerosene,
and paid only 60 centavos per liter as excise tax (one peso is
equal to 100 centavos). The excise tax for jet fuel is 3.67 pesos
per liter (one U.S. dollar is equal to 40 pesos).
</P>
<P>
Rualo said that the government is being defrauded of revenues
estimated at 2 billion pesos (50 million dollars) to 3 billion
pesos (75 million dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
Excise tax is collected by the government on alcohol, tobacco
and petroleum products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
