<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gap Between Rich and Poor in Vietnam Widens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The average incomes in Vietnam
are rising but the gap between rich and poor is growing, Vietnam's
English daily Vietnam News reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A survey, conducted in cooperation with the World Bank, the
United Nations Development Program and Swedish International
Development Agency, showed that average per capita income across
all sectors of the country is now 3.465 Vietnamese dong (VND) (248
U.S. dollars) a year, a 250 percent increase over 1993's figure.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that average urban income among the 6,000
households questioned is 9.057 million VND (648 U.S. dollars) a
year, a 3.7-fold increase over 1993, while rural incomes have
increased two-fold to 2.544 million VND (182 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The percentage of households suffering food shortages fell from
20-25 percent in 1992-1993 to almost 15 percent in 1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
The survey also reveals that increased incomes have resulted in
a significant improvement in living standards, with spending power
up 140 percent in the five years from 1993 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, despite these positive results the survey exposes a
widening gap between rich and poor, with the highest income group
earning 11 times more than the lowest. In 1996, the figure was a
mere 2.8 times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
