<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Will Pay Less Interest Tax Than Rich: Vice-Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Despite their fears to the
contrary low income people in China will have more to gain than
lose under the new tax on savings interest scheme, Vice-Minister
of Finance Gao Qiang said here today.
</P>
<P>
The proposed 20-percent tax rate on savings interest will mean
a cut of the interest rate by 0.45 percentage points, he explained
in a news release.
</P>
<P>
According to Gao, the tax, which was approved by the National
People's Congress, China's legislature, on Monday, is expected to
boost the government's coffers by an additional 20 to 30 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that low income people will suffer a certain loss
of interest due to the new tax. However, he stressed that since
the bulk of the country's nearly 6,000 billion yuan of savings
deposits are owned by a small group of people, it will be the rich
who bear the lion's share of the tax.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the government intends to use the money
raised by the new tax solely to improve the living standards of
low income people, including raising allowances for laid off
workers, increasing pensions for retired people and lifting the
minimum level of subsistence for urban residents.
</P>
<P>
"As a consequence low income people will have more to gain once
these new measures are introduced," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the government is also considering reducing or
exempting interest tax on savings deposits when they are used for
education insurance, housing funds, pension or unemployment
insurance.
</P>
<P>
China has slashed interest rates from over nine percent to the
current 2.25 percent over the past two years. However, it has
failed to reverse the falling trend in investment growth and
sluggish consumption even though prices have been falling for more
than 20 consecutive months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
