<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria begins troops withdrawal From S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria Tuesday formally began
its troops pullout from Sierra Leone, a Nigerian newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of Nigeria's 2,000 contingent of the Economic
Community of West African States peace force (ECOMOG) were
airlifted out of the country Tuesday, according to the Guardian
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister, Dapo Sarumi, last week said that
Nigeria's 12,000- strong contingent in the ECOMOG force would be
airlifted in phases at a rate of 2,000 troops a month.
</P>
<P>
However, a battalion will be left behind for the modified role
of disarming and ensuring security in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The pullout is expected to last six months, during which period
some 750 civilians stranded in Sierra Leone would be stripped
home, the minister had said.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian troop's withdrawal is mainly based on financial
considerations. Nigeria has been repeatedly calling for the
United Nations to take over its peace- keeping role in S. Leone.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian troop serves the backbone of the 14,000-strong
ECOMOG force,
</P>
<P>
which moved into Sierra Leone from Liberia in the middle of 1997
to support the elected President Tejan kabbah, who was ousted
earlier by a coup of the country's military junta. Since the late
1997, the ECOMOG force had been fighting with S. Leone rebels,
until the June cease-fire this year before a peace agreement was
reached in Togo's capital Lome ending the country's nine-year
civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
