<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Rejects Establishment of Humanitarian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Angola refused on Tuesday a
proposal of establishing humanitarian corridors for helping
impoverished population in the interior rural areas, saying that
"a majority of those impoverished people are in zones under the
government administration."
</P>
<P>
Angolan Minister of Assistance and Reintegration was quoted
here on Wednesday by local press as saying that the flow of
population from the rural area to the cities was a pity, because
they were forced to leave their rural areas by the rebels with an
aim to create problems in the cities controlled by the government
troops.
</P>
<P>
As for those living in the areas controlled by the rebels, the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA),
Albino Malungo said, " there lives only a small amount of people,
without humanitarian crisis, for they are working in the forest or
the agricultural areas."
</P>
<P>
The minister said that only when the rebels stop attacking the
humanitarian columns can the non-government organizations (NGOs)
enter those areas.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, who recently made a visit to Geneva,
Swiss, the humanitarian situation in Angola has "changed a lot"
and the country is expected to obtain more humanitarian
assistance.
</P>
<P>
As for the increase of the number of displaced families and
abandoned children in Luanda, capital of Angola, Malungo said it
was due to "the afflux of the people searching for security."
</P>
<P>
On the issue of reinstallation of agriculture, Malungo
expressed his anxiety over the problem of the grain seeds, saying
that the people have few means of production as the agricultural
period is approaching.
</P>
<P>
But Malungo said he believes the agricultural period will not
be missed since Angola has gained the support from some NGOs, such
as "Save the Children" and the United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF), which have provided the rural residents with seeds and
other agricultural materials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
