<HEADLINE> 21 Political Parties Gain Seats in Indonesian House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A total of 21 of the 48
political parties which contested the June general election gained
seats in the House of Representatives (DPR), the Indonesian
Election Committee (PPI) announced here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This was decided by the PPI at its plenary meeting here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Election winner Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P)
would have 153 seats in the new house, becoming the single biggest
party in the DPR.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Golkar Party came in second with 120 seats, followed
by the United Development Party with 58 seats, the National
Awakening Party 51 seats, the National Mandate Party 34 seats, the
Crescent Star Party 13 seats and the Justice Party seven seats.
</P>
<P>
Forty-eight political parties took part in the general election
on June 7 to compete for 462 of the 500 seats in the house. The
remaining 38 seats are reserved for the military, whose members do
not vote.
</P>
<P>
It was announced that new members of the DPR and the People's
Consultative Assembly (MPR) will be installed between October 1
and 3.
</P>
<P>
The MPR, the country's highest decision-making body, will meet
in November to elect the country's next president. It will
comprise the DPR members plus 200 appointed regional and interest
groups' representatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
