<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Li People See Earth-Shaking Changes On Southern Island Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, September 1 (Xinhua) -- To the Li people, who are the
aborigines of China's island province Hainan, earth-shaking
changes have taken place since the founding of the People's
Republic and after Hainan became a province in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Hainan is the country's largest special economic zone. It has 7.
43 million people, 1.24 million of them from various ethnic groups,
including 1.14 million Li and 60,000 Miao.
</P>
<P>
Before New China was founded in 1949, most of the Li lived deep
in the island's mountains and led a miserable life, with not
enough to eat and wear. But New China brought development
opportunities to Hainan and good fortune to the islanders. From
1988 to 1998, the Central Government and Hainan Provincial
Government spent well over 22.6 billion yuan in improving
infrastructure in areas inhabited by ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
The completed projects include the eastern expressway from
Haikou, the provincial capital, to Sanya, a popular tourist
destination on the southern tip of the island; an international
airport in Sanya; and a great number of new berths for ships.
</P>
<P>
The improved infrastructure allowed ethnic groups to use a
billion U.S. dollars of overseas investment for 900 projects.
Areas that had no industries now have industrial enterprises like
the Hainan Natural Gas Chemical Fertilizer Plant, tropical cash
crops, and tourism in Sanya and Tongshi.
</P>
<P>
By 1998, the GDP of the areas was 10 billion yuan and the
number of people living in poverty went down to 250,000 from 870,
000, while the per capita income of farmers was 1,318 yuan and
most rural residents no longer lived in mud huts and had moved
into spacious brick housing.
</P>
<P>
The Li people's ideas have also changed dramatically and they
no longer look down on commerce and have learned how to do
business and promote themselves.
</P>
<P>
Five years ago, Li Dehui, a Li farmer from Sanya, was praised
for being able to make 70,000 yuan annually during a visit by
President Jiang Zemin to the island.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
