<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Negotiator Claims End to Talks Over Wye </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 1 (Xinhua) - Following his meeting with
Palestinian officials, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's envoy
Gilad Sher said Tuesday that from the Israeli respective, the
talks with the Palestinians over the implementation of Wye accord
is over.
</P>
<P>
Sher said that no further meeting has been planned between
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators.
</P>
<P>
Sher noted Barak may announce in his cabinet meeting later
on Tuesday that the Palestinians are interested in the
implementation of the "original" Wye agreement, which means it
will be carried out according to Israeli interpretation.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have been engaged in intensified efforts to
reach an agreement on Israeli proposals over the modification of
the Wye interim agreement before United States Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright starts a visit to the region on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The main issues blocking a breakthrough were the release of
Palestinian prisoners and the timetable for Israeli troop
redeployments in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians demand that Israel release 650 political
prisoners, those jailed for anti-Israel activities, but Israel
insists that it will release only 500 prisoners and will not
free those Palestinians involved in killings of Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Barak has proposed to postpone the last of the three
stages of troop withdrawals stipulated in the Wye accord until
February next year, when the two sides are supposed to have
worked out a framework for the final-status talks, which deal
with thorny issues like Jerusalem and Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinians want Israel to complete all the troop
withdrawals at an earlier date in line with the original
timetable of the Wye accord, which calls on Israel to hand
over 13 percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians in
three stages over a period of 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
Barak's hard-line predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu carried out
the first stage of the agreement late last year before
freezing it in a failed attempt to woo back rebellious
coalition partners opposed to territorial concession to the
Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Welcomes Contacts With US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam welcomes all contacts
with the United States in order to increase mutual understanding
and broaden equal cooperation between the two countries, a
spokeswoman of the Vietnamese Foreign Ministry said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a press briefing Wednesday afternoon, spokeswoman Phan Thuy
Thanh announced that U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
will pay an official visit to Vietnam on September 6 and 7.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Thanh said, Albright will have talks with
Vietnam's Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Nguyen Manh
Cam and will meet with Vietnamese leaders.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers will exchange views on issues relating to the
bilateral relations as well as regional and international issues
of mutual interest.
</P>
<P>
The two sides may sign an agreement on cooperation in science
and technology during Albright's visit, the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
On the signing of a Vietnamese-U.S. bilateral trade agreement,
Thanh said experts of the two countries are making efforts to
finalize the agreement text in order to submit it to the
governments and bodies concerned of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman also announced that Vietnamese Prime Minister
Phan Van Khai will attend the APEC leadership meeting scheduled to
be held in New Zealand on September 12 and 13.
</P>
<P>
Concerning Vietnam's attitude toward the APEC meeting, Thanh
said APEC members need to further strengthen their technical and
economic cooperation in order to continue helping members which
still are affected by the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam holds the view that the APEC meeting should call for
intensifying technical and economic cooperation in the APEC in
order to overcome the consequences of the crisis, the spokeswoman
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
