<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Investigating Blast in Central Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian investigators are
probing two leads in an explosion Tuesday evening that rocked
Moscow's Okhotny Ryad shopping center near the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Investigators from the Federal Security Service (FSB), the main
successor to the Soviet KGB, have postulated links between the
bombing and the latest events in the Caucasus, as well as to
extremist organizations, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Dagestani separatists have threatened to carry out terrorist
acts inside Russia in the wake of the federal forces' successful
operation in the Caucasus, Interfax quoted FSB sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, police have found at the scene of the explosion a
flyer claimed to be written by a "Revolutionary Writers Union," an
organization not heard of before.
</P>
<P>
A total of 41 people were injured in the "Dynamite" electronic
gaming arcade on the third level of the mall at around 20:00 local
time Tuesday. Twenty-four people, five of them children, remain
hospitalized. Nine are described as in serious condition with
wounds received from flying glass and game machine fragments.
</P>
<P>
The flyer denounces consumerism and hails "city guerrilla
warfare" aimed at creating a "revolutionary situation" in the
country, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
"Actions similar to today's create a certain social machine, of
which just experimental samples have been demonstrated. It will
gradually gain the status of a real public factor," the flyer said.
</P>
<P>
"Messrs Consumers," the flyer said, "we do not like your way of
life and it is not safe for you!"
</P>
<P>
In addition, authorities are also looking for "purely criminal
reasons" or simple hooliganism behind the blast, which happened
just several dozen meters from the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Law enforcement departments have stepped up security in the
capital and the search for the perpetuators of the blast will be
carried out in Moscow over the next two days.
</P>
<P>
Companies likely to be stocking explosives and other dangerous
substances will be checked. Venues will be thoroughly examined for
suspicious objects before large sporting, cultural and political
events.
</P>
<P>
Authorities will also instruct the public on what to do when
they spot suspicious objects in stores, the metro and on public
transport, Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
