<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pillar of China's National Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Editor's note: This year
marks the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's
Republic of China. Over the past five decades, China's
achievements in all economic sectors have attracted worldwide
attention.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua News Agency is to release about 20 stories about the
nation's economy. The first of the series was released on August
17. This is the twelfth.
</P>
<P>
A latest report from the Chinese Ministry of Agriculture
indicates that China's rural businesses are expected to enjoy
higher growth this year than last year, with their total added
output value exceeding 2,500 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months of this year, the total added output
value of these businesses reached 1,406.2 billion yuan, up 16.7
percent over the same 1998 period, with profits and taxes rising
16.6 percent and 15.6 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 50 years, and especially since 1978, the rural
businesses have witnessed remarkable development and constituted
the main part of rural economy, representing almost half of the
nation's industrial sector and become a pillar of the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
The National Bureau of Statistics indicates that in 1998, the
rural businesses realised an added output value of 2,218 billion
yuan, accounting for 27.9 percent of the nation's gross domestic
product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, such businesses contributed one-fifth of the total
national tax revenues and 34.8 percent of the country's total
exports.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the rural businesses are the fast-growing part
of the economy as a whole, although they have experienced ups and
downs.
</P>
<P>
In the 1950s and 1960s, farmers began inviting some retired
engineers from cities to set up simple workshops, and by the end
of 1959, they had established more than 700,000 small workshops
and plants, employing some five million people.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of 1978 when China's reform and opening up
policies were introduced, thousands of agricultural workers, freed
from farming, have cast off the bondage of the planned-economy and
established market-oriented businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pillar of China's National Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
From 1984 to 1988, such enterprises reached the first stage of
overall rapid development and their number exceeded 18 million,
employing 95.46 million people.
</P>
<P>
In the following three years, the fast growth trend of the
rural businesses slowed down partly as a result of over supply in
the market.
</P>
<P>
The second boom time for the rural businesses came in 1992 when
the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping stressed their importance
during his major tour of southern China.
</P>
<P>
In the same year, the rural businesses grew in output value by
54.7 percent over the previous year with their total added output
value hitting 1,797.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
After 1995, such businesses entered a period of stable
development. Despite huge difficulties in both domestic and
overseas markets last year, the rural businesses still enjoyed a
17.3 percent rise in added output value over the previous year, 9.
5 percentage points higher than the nation's GDP.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the rural businesses, an imaginative creation
of Chinese farmers, have played a pivotal role in optimizing the
structure of the rural economy, supporting agricultural
development and increasing farmers' income.
</P>
<P>
Twenty years ago, the added output value of these businesses
only accounted for less than a quarter of the total production and
services output value in rural areas, but in 1987 it exceeded the
total rural agricultural output value, making up 52.4 percent of
the total rural production and services output value.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pillar of China's National Economy (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The booming rural businesses have also become a major source of
investment in agriculture, and last year, the collectively-owned
rural businesses alone provided 6.4 billion yuan for the
development of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
With the rise of farming efficiency a considerable number of
surplus rural laborers were thrown onto the market, and the rural
businesses again became a major source of employment for them.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in 1998, China had more than 20 million
rural businesses employing near 130 million people, an increase of
3.4 times over the 1978 figure.
</P>
<P>
While the rural businesses provide more job opportunities for
rural surplus laborers, they also helped boost the rise of farmers
' income. In 1998, the annual per capita income of workers in such
businesses quadrupled that in 1978, standing at over 4,000 yuan,
and one-third of farmers' income come from these businesses.
</P>
<P>
The growth of the rural businesses has also boosted the
urbanization of rural areas. In 1998, the number of cities and
towns established with government approval surpassed 19,000,
accommodating 150 million rural residents.
</P>
<P>
Chinese people are paying increasing attention to the
development of the rural businesses, as their performance will
have a direct impact on the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate that if such businesses grow in added output
value by 3 percentage points, the nation's GDP will rise by one
percentage point.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace to Prevail in Middle East: Israeli Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Peace will eventually prevail in
the Middle East region though the road to the peace is long, a top
Israeli official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Egypt's Voice of Arabs radio, Israeli
Deputy Foreign Minister Nawaf Mosalhah expressed hope that Arab
countries and Israel will reactivate peace talks in a bid to
realize just and durable peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Since his election in May, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
has expressed readiness repeatedly to resume negotiations with
Syria. Damascus has responded positively.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' talks came to a halt in early 1996 over the
future of the Golan Heights which Israel captured from Syria in
the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel are holding intensive talks for a
timetable for Israeli troops pullback from part of the West Bank
and the release of hundreds of Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The two issues are major parts of the Wye Accord signed last
October, under which Israel should pull out its troops from
another 13 percent of the West Bank. Israel suspended the accord
in early December only after handing over 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Mosalhah was appointed by Barak last month as deputy foreign
minister, the most senior post Arabs have ever taken in the
government of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Mosalhah contended that the implementation of the Wye accord
does not constitute a problem in the Palestinian-Israeli talks,
but the final status talks will mostly challenge the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The final status talks will tackle thorny issues including the
fate of Jerusalem, Jewish settlements, Palestinian refugees and
the Palestinian statehood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
