<HEADLINE> Japan, Russia Ink Accord on Free Isle Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Japan and Russia on Wednesday
agreed to allow former Japanese residents of disputed Russian-held
islands off Hokkaido to visit the islands freely.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during a meeting between Japanese
Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura and Russian First Deputy Prime
Minister Viktor Khristenko, who arrived here Tuesday for a four-
day visit.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers "reached a final accord and agreed to
exchange a verbal note Thursday" for free access to the disputed
islands of Etorofu, Shikotan, Kunashiri and the Habomai group of
islets, a Japanese government official told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, former Japanese inhabitants, their spouses
and children will be able to visit the islands anytime they wish
using identification papers. They will not be required to hold
passports and to go through immigration procedures.
</P>
<P>
The disputed islands off Japan's northernmost Hokkaido were
seized by Soviet troops at the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
The agreed free access is a step beyond the current visa-free
arrangement under which Tokyo and Moscow do not require visas for
Japanese and Russian visitors participating in government-arranged
exchange programs to and from the disputed islands.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi made the proposal for free
access during his trip to Moscow in last November.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Komura also reiterated that Japan has
decided to resume and soon disburse 1.1 billion dollars in untied
loans to Russia through the Export-Import Bank of Japan, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi announced his decision to resume the loans on Tuesday in
a meeting with Khristenko.
</P>
<P>
The loans are part of 1.5 billion dollars in untied Ex-Im Bank
credit Japan pledged in February last year to extend by the end of
1999 under a co-financing scheme with the World Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
