<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Seeks Public Views on 2000 LegCo Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Electoral Affairs
Commission of Hong Kong announced Wednesday that it will launch a
public consultation program later this month to seek views on the
Legislative Council election in 2000.
</P>
<P>
On the basis on the public opinions, the commission will put
forward its final recommendations to the chief executive by the
end of October this year.
</P>
<P>
Under the Legislative Council (Amendment) Ordinance 1999, the
number of members to be returned for the geographical
constituencies has increased by four to 24 and each constituency
is to elect between four and six members.
</P>
<P>
The commission proposes that Hong Kong Island and New
Territories East constituencies will each have five seats, Kowloon
West and Kowloon East will each have four seats and New
Territories West six seats.
</P>
<P>
Woo Kwok-hing, chairman of the commission, said at a press
conference Wednesday that the commission must observe several
statutory criteria for making recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The population of each constituency is a primary consideration,
he said, and in addition, each constituency is to be formed by two
or more contiguous whole District Council constituencies.
</P>
<P>
The commission shall have regard to the existing boundaries of
districts, the existing boundaries of the Municipal Council areas,
community identities, the preservation of local ties and physical
features of the relevant areas.
</P>
<P>
According to the government forecast, Hong Kong will have a
population of 6,736,900 by the end of March 2000. It follows that
each of the 24 seats will cater for 280,704 people.
</P>
<P>
The commission has drawn up a provisional recommendation that
delineation and names of the existing five geographical
constituencies may remain the same in the 2000 Legislative Council
election, except minor adjustments to the boundaries of four
constituencies in Kowloon and the New Territories as a result of
district developments.
</P>
<P>
Woo said, "We consider it proper to maintain the existing
boundaries and names because electors have got used to them."
</P>
<P>
"Our recommendations are drawn up with an objective and fair
method and fully meet all the statutory criteria. Political
influence or advantage plays no part at all in our decisions," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The commission will meet the public at a public forum on
September 27 to listen to their views. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Timor's Ballot Vote Count Starts on Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Mission in East Timor
(UNAMET) is scheduled to begin its vote count on Friday after it
completes its reconciliation count on Thursday, UNAMET deputy
chief Carlos Valenzuella said in Dili, capital of East Timor,
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The reconciliation count, which aims to cross-check the number
of ballots from the ballot boxes against the number of ballots
issued by the UNAMET, began on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The reconciliation count will be concluded in two days,
Valenzuella was quoted by the Antara News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
After the reconciliation count, he said, all the ballot papers
will be mixed together so that it would be impossible to detect
which vote dominated which district.
</P>
<P>
"This is a sensitive period, thus we urge various parties,
particularly the Indonesian Police, to secure it," Valenzuella
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Antara, the reconciliation count is being
witnessed by independent domestic and foreign observers,
representatives of the Indonesian and Portuguese governments and
UNAMET officials.
</P>
<P>
He further said representatives of East Timor's warring
pro-autonomy and pro-independence factions did not show up at the
count.
</P>
<P>
"What is important is that representatives of Indonesia and
Portugal came," he added.
</P>
<P>
UNAMET spokesman Ueki Yoshiro meanwhile said some 45 military
liaison officers arrived in Dili from Darwin, Australia, on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 45 officers, consisting of 27 Australians and 18
Pakistanis, will join the present 50 military liaison officers.
</P>
<P>
The UNAMET has reduced the number of its voluntary staff
members gradually, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 57 U.N. volunteers left for Darwin on Tuesday while 118
others are scheduled to leave on Wednesday and 135 more on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The UNAMET is maintaining 100 personnel to help in the vote
count, Yoshiro was quoted by Antara as saying.
</P>
<P>
Some 450,000 East Timorese cast their votes in the August 30
U.N.-sponsored ballot that will decide the political future of
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The ballot was to determine whether East Timor, a former
Portuguese colony, will enjoy wide-ranging autonomy within
Indonesia or get independence. East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976, but the move was never recognized by the United
Nations. 
</P>
