<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 08:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian, French FMs Discuss Mideast Peace on Phone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa has held a telephone conversation with his French
counterpart Hubert Vedrine on the Mideast peace process as part of
the continued consultations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Al-Akhbar daily reported Wednesday that Moussa called
Vedrine Tuesday night to brief him on the latest developments
in the peace talks between the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Moussa updated Vedrine with fresh efforts aimed at pushing the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks forward, especially the ongoing
negotiations for an agreement on the implementation of the Wye
Accord signed last October, the pro-government newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The conversation came after a visit to Egypt by Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Arafat met with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in the
Mediterranean port city of Alexandria Tuesday and the two leaders
discussed the Palestinian-Israeli talks before the Mideast tour of
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright starting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian and Israeli negotiators are trying to set a
timetable for the last two of the three-phased Israeli troops
withdrawal from another 11 percent of the West Bank and reach an
agreement on the release of hundreds of Palestinian political
prisoners held in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
Moussa's phone call fell within the context of the continued
coordination between Egypt and France on all issues of mutual
interests, foremost the Middle East peace process, an Egyptian
Foreign Ministry source said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with
Israel, is an active mediator between Arab countries and
Israel. France, which maintains close political relations with
Egypt, wants to play a key role in the Mideast peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic-language newspaper said the two ministers agreed to
meet in September for more coordination in New York on the
sidelines of the United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine is scheduled to visit Egypt in autumn as part of a
multi-leg tour of the Middle East, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
