<HEADLINE> Philippines to Go On Cracking Down on Armed Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said Wednesday that his government will continue to go
hard on armed groups bent on challenging its authority and the
law.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a weekly radio program, Estrada said the heavy
casualties sustained by extremists who kidnapped a four-year-old
girl in the southern Philippine island of Mindanao were proof of
this resolve.
</P>
<P>
The president reiterated the warning he issued in late July in
his State of the Nation Address against armed groups that there
would be punishment for rebellion.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 extremists were reportedly killed in a recent
military offensive against the extremists' stronghold in the
outskirts of Basilan, Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The government operations resulted in the release of
four-year-old Wilmarie Furlgay, granddaughter of a former mayor of
Lamitan.
</P>
<P>
Wilmarie was kidnapped on August 11 in front of her parents'
store in downtown Lamitan. Her abductors initially demanded 3
million pesos (75,000 U.S. Dollars) and 100 head of cattle as
ransom.
</P>
<P>
The president has repeatedly stressed that while his
administration is open to peace talks with rebel groups, it will
not tolerate their criminal acts or violation of the constitution
and the law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
