<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Holds Drills to Mark Disaster Prevention Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Japan's central and local
governments held drills Wednesday to mark Disaster Prevention Day
in a bid to prepare people for the possible occurrence of a major
earthquake, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
A total of 5.7 million people, including firefighters and
medical personnel as well as those in charge of public utilities
such as electricity and gas, took part in the drills, which
focused on information communication and guiding evacuees, Kyodo
said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese central government conducted its drills in Fuji,
Shizuoka Prefecture, and in Tokyo, drawing on scenarios based on
an earthquake hitting the Tokai region and on a direct hit in the
Kanto area.
</P>
<P>
Many of the drills held this year placed emphasis on securing
communication links by such means as teleconference systems
receiving pictures from earthquake response centers and
helicopters using satellites.
</P>
<P>
The drills also incorporated practical exercises such as
dispatching medical teams to the theoretical disaster site.
</P>
<P>
The drills in Tokyo began in the afternoon with an alert that a
quake measuring 7.2 on the open-ended Richter scale had just
struck central Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Boarding a helicopter in front of the Imperial Palace, Japanese
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi proceeded to the drill area to take
command of crisis management efforts.
</P>
<P>
Envisioning transport disruptions, some 550 participants were
asked to walk seven kilometers from the Yurakucho district to the
drill site while the Self-Defense Forces (SDF) warships were sent
to ferry stranded commuters to their homes via Tokyo Bay.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in Hyogo Prefecture, southwestern Japan, where 6,400
people died in the 1995 Great Hanshin Earthquake, about 62,000
people participated in drills which hypothesized an earthquake
registering an upper 6 on the 7-point Japanese seismic scale
centering on Himeji.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Disaster Prevention Day commemorates the Great Kanto
Earthquake, which struck the Kanto area, centering on Tokyo, on
September 1, 1923. The powerful quake measuring 7.9 on the Ritcher
scale killed 140,000 people and injured 100,000 others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
