<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rebound, Dollar Falls in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rebounded sharply
in Tokyo Wednesday, boosted by bargain-hunting following their
sharp decline the previous day.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, which plunged 482.41 points
on Tuesday, recovered 365.92 points, or 2.10 percent, to 17,802.48.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, rose 39.22 points or 2.69 percent to 1,496.
24.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section came to 612.57 million shares,
down from 709.21 million shares Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Toshiba Corp. was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors, the major driving force in the Tokyo stock
market, were net buyers throughout the day, encouraging domestic
investors to buy stocks, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Share prices were higher in most business sectors, with the
export-oriented electric machinery sector rising 1.56 percent
despite the yen's strength.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers far
outnumbered losers 765 to 440, with 119 issues ending unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar fell against the
yen in a market that lacked a clear sense of direction.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was quoted at 109.21-24 yen at 5 p.m., down
from 109.76-79 yen at 9 a.m., and from 109.70-80 in New York late
Tuesday. It was traded at 110.17-20 yen in Tokyo late Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
