<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Children's Situation Worrying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Forty percent of Zambian
children are chronically malnourished resulting in excessive
intellectual damage, the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF)
has said.
</P>
<P>
The situation of Zambian children and youths was threatened as
never before, Zambian UNICEF representative Peter Mcdermott told a
consultative meeting of co-operating partners here.
</P>
<P>
Infant mortality is estimated at 112 among every 1,000 children
in the country, Mcdermott was quoted by Wednesday's Zambian
newspaper, the Post, as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Most children in Zambia never reach their sixth birthday. The
government, in fact, estimates that about 50,000 children are born
with HIV/ AIDS each year," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mcdermott said over 600,000 children managing to reach the age
of five in a healthy state have never attended the primary school,
while for thousands more the quality of education is such that
learning is limited.
</P>
<P>
Those who survive these perils would still live to face the
vice of sexual abuse, forced or exploitative labor, a life in
conflict with the law spent on the streets and the reality of
abandoned children who often grow into disaffected homeless
youths, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Hundreds of thousands of others are brought up in households
of chronic sickness and death doing untold psychological damage
to the young child," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consultative Commission Set Up in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Mission in East Timor
(UNAMET) Wednesday announced the establishment of a Consultative
Commission for East Timor Reconciliation in Dili, capital of East
Timor, the Antara News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The consultative commission is formally established, although
there are some problems that have halted the announcement of its
membership," deputy spokesman for UNAMET Ueki Yoshiro said.
</P>
<P>
The commission, whose establishment was proposed by U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan, has 25 members, including 10
representatives of the pro-integration camp, 10 of the
pro-independence camp and five appointed by the U.N. secretary
general.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting on the establishment of the commission was
held on Tuesday and attended by six members of the
pro-independence group and some pro-integrationists who were
nominated as members of the commission.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, four supporters of integration said they would
resign from the commission if the UNAMET can not clarify
allegations of impropriety during the direct ballot on August 30.
</P>
<P>
East Timorese Pro-Integration Joint Front spokesman Basilio
Dias Araujo has said his organization recorded at least 37
violations during the ballot.
</P>
<P>
He charged that most of the violations were committed by UNAMET
personnel, who he said compelled voters to choose independence
over autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Yoshiro said he did not yet receive the statement of the four
members and UNAMET chief Ian Martin asserted that no members of
the commission will resign.
</P>
<P>
According to the UNAMET, 98.6 percent of the registered voters
in East Timor took part in the direct ballot.
</P>
<P>
The ballot was to determine whether East Timor, a former
Portuguese colony, will enjoy wide-ranging autonomy within
Indonesia or get independence. East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976, but the move was never recognized by the United
Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
