<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Tomato Ban Might Squash Deals with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Agriculture Ministry
has warned that if local tomato farmers insist on banning the
import of Jordanian tomatoes, Lebanon's export deals with Jordan
will be also canceled.
</P>
<P>
Fakhr Dakroub, a senior official at the ministry, said that
banning Jordanian tomatoes would be a blow to Lebanon, the Daily
Star reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"How can the farmers ask us to ban the import of tomatoes while
Lebanon sells large quantities of apple and potato to Jordan,"
Dakroub added.
</P>
<P>
According to existing agreements, Lebanon exports potatoes and
apples to Jordan and imports a variety of vegetables.
</P>
<P>
A delegation from southern Lebanon has met Agriculture Minister
Suleiman Franjieh to ask him to protect Lebanese agricultural
produce.
</P>
<P>
The farmers claim that importing tomatoes to Lebanon does not
make sense because the country is sitting on a surplus of domestic
tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
"We produce 300,000 tons of tomatoes each year, half of which
are dumped or sold at very cheap prices," said Waddah Fakhri, head
of the Southern Farmers Association.
</P>
<P>
According to Fakhri, many local farmers are selling 25
kilograms of tomatoes for just 5,000 Lebanese pounds (about 3.33
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He proposed that Jordan export wheat, fertilizers and other
products that are not available in Lebanon, a demand which has
been rejected by Jordan.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the Lebanese government to subsidize the cost
of fruit and vegetables grown by Lebanese farmers.
</P>
<P>
"Other countries do this and it would only cost the government
about 50 million dollars a year," Fakhri added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
