<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Urge Debt Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- All the debt owed by Africa to
the donor community should be scrapped, a high-level seminar on
Africa's debt urged in a statement.
</P>
<P>
President of Botswana Festus Mogae, also chairman of the
two-day seminar, said Tuesday that African governments were ready
to accept conditions for the debt reprieve but noted that the
conditions should be discussed and agreed on by parties affected
instead of only the donor countries.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Times daily Wednesday quoted Mogae as saying that
African governments must fulfil the conditions given by the donors
and creditor countries if they expect to benefit from the
anticipated debt relief.
</P>
<P>
"African countries must undertake the fundamental changes that
will make further assistance available," he said.
</P>
<P>
These changes include trade liberalization, civil service
restructuring, a working judiciary, democratization, respect for
human rights and improved infrastructure, the president said.
</P>
<P>
Africa faces a total debt of 285 billion U.S. dollars,
representing more than 200 percent of Africa's exports, according
to World Bank statistics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Speaker Calls for Coexistence in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Speaker Humayun
Rasheed Chowdhury on Wednesday called for "tremendous efforts" to
consolidate peaceful coexistence in Asia and challenge the threats
to peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
The speaker made the call here at the inaugural session of the
four-day "Asian Parliamentarians' Conference for Peace and
Cooperation," which was initiated by Bangladesh early this year to
identify the role of parliamentarians in creating and promoting an
atmosphere of peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We need peace to build up justice for the vast masses of
citizens throughout the world who live their lives in poverty...
The only battle we should be fighting is the battle for the
dignity of our people and for development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentarians, as "the formal, legal and institutional
representatives of the people," have the capacity and the duty of
voicing the opinions of the peoples they represent, said the
speaker.
</P>
<P>
"We will all be responsible for taking the decisions and we
should always consider those who will bear the burden of our wrong
decisions, and who will need to endure more in the absence of
peace," Chowdhury pointed out.
</P>
<P>
In Asia, he said, "we must make tremendous efforts to
consolidate our peaceful coexistence and to challenge the threats
to peace that are present in our continent." "We need to prevent,
resolve and transform violent conflict that... causes suffering to
our peoples."
</P>
<P>
"We want to intensify our efforts for the cause of peace... We
need to know better what are the deep causes of war to enroot the
culture of peace... We want to renew our commitments to
disarmament and human security. And we want to strengthen the
rights of our peoples," he said.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the conference, Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina said, "We assembled here today to see our continent emerge
in the 21st century as the continent that will have its presence
felt and its voice heard all over the world."
</P>
<P>
"Peace is an all-embracing state, a state in which the woes
that afflict human life would be banished once and for all. Peace
is the state that guarantees economic and social emancipation and
generates friendship between all," she said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said there are differences on some issues
between countries, "but we are here to make a collective and
concerted effort for peace," not to highlight the differences.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Chinese delegation Zeng Jianhui, member of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC) of
China and chairman of the NPC Foreign Affairs Committee, delivered
a speech on behalf of all the parliamentary delegations attending
the conference.
</P>
<P>
Former Indian Prime Minister I.K. Gujral, Pakistani Speaker
Illahi Bukhsh Soomro and representative of the U.N. Development
Program in Bangladesh David E. Lockwood also spoke at the opening
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from 33 Asian countries, including Bangladesh,
China, Indonesia, Cambodia, Indonesia, Malaysia, Pakistan, South
Korea, Thailand and Vietnam, are participating in the conference
funded by the Bangladeshi government and the U.N. Development
Program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
