<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Improve Power Capacity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenya Power and Lighting
Company (KPLC) has taken new measures to sustain adequate
electricity generation capacity to its 480,000 customers in the
country following the liberalization of the power sector.
</P>
<P>
A press statement issued Tuesday by KPLC said that to improve
power supply, the company had entered into power purchase
agreements with various power-generating companies including the
independent power producers, the government-run Kenya Times
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The liberalization of the sector will help alleviate power
shortage by encouraging private investors to take up the
challenge of generating  enough power to meet local needs, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Over the next five years, Kenya Electricity Generating Company
(KenGen) will build power projects with a total capacity of 254
megawatts, and one of its projects, the Sondu Miriu hydropower
station with a capacity of 60 megawatts in Nyanza Province in
southwestern Kenya, is now under construction, the KPLC said.
</P>
<P>
Completing with KenGen in the liberalized power supply sector
are also two independent power producers including the Tsavo
Power Company in Coast Province in eastern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
KPLC said by 2002, Kenya would envisage 503 megawatts of
additional electricity capacity to be commissioned under the
committed projects.
</P>
<P>
According to KPLC, the country's current peak demand stands at
760 megawatts as against available capacity of 676.5 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
Just a week ago, KPLC announced to start power rationing
nationwide from September 1 following the low water level in the
country's three main energy reservoirs as a result of the dry
spell during the long rains season between March and June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Meeting of Prosecutors Scheduled for Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The International Association
of Prosecutors (IAP) will hold its 4th annual meeting from
September 5 to 10 in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 400 prosecutors, 51 of them attorney generals and 24
deputy attorney generals, from 81 countries, regions and
international organizations are expected to attend, according to
Zhang Qiong, a deputy procurator-general and chairman of the
Chinese organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
The participants will discuss investigating and prosecuting
cases of fraud and corruption and professional ethics and
responsibilities, Zhang told a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The IAP was founded in June 1995 in Vienna. The Chinese
Association of Prosecutors was one of the founders. It now has 58
member organizations and more than 600 individual members. Its
purpose is to promote prosecutorial rights, supervise criminal
proceedings, and increase cooperation among prosecutors and legal
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The association has played an active role in promoting
cooperation among prosecutors and curbing domestic violence and
international and organized crimes, Zhang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Puts Zero Tariff Loss at 2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Loss of revenue as a result of
implementation of zero tariff in the Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) region is estimated at an average of two
percent.
</P>
<P>
While addressing the COMESA Rules of Origin Workshop here
Tuesday, Secretary General Erastus Mwencha said the regional body
is currently undertaking studies to determine the actual loss of
each member when the zero tariff is implemented next year.
</P>
<P>
"We also hope to explore ways of addressing the expected
losses. For example, the loss can be compensated through increased
trade and improved efficiency in revenue collection as well as
diversification of revenue sources," he was quoted by Wednesday's
Zambian newspaper, the Post, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the timing or speed at which COMESA is moving toward
a free trade area, Mwencha said the tariff reduction program began
in 1984 and it was originally intended that by 1992 the free trade
area would have been established.
</P>
<P>
"However, member states requested for an extension up to the
year 2000, giving a total of 16 years," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said given the globalization process, other trade regimes
provided for less than ten years transition period to a free trade
area and the on- going debate should concentrate on the benefits
of free trade area.
</P>
<P>
"The reason for market integration is to create a large market
that will attract investment and enable the region to utilize the
local resources and to integrate into the global economy," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha said a free trade area would also lead to increased
competitiveness of the local industry and consumers would stand to
benefit in terms of price and quality of products.
</P>
<P>
He explained that representatives of the private sector from
each COMESA country have been invited to the workshop as the rules
of origin will have a direct impact on intra-regional trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Post Should Focus on Customer Value: Anderson Consulting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua)-- The advance of information
technology will greatly broaden the borders of traditional postal
services instead of squeezing them out of the market, says an
international expert on posts and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Christopher Brennan, a partner in the Anderson consulting of
the United States, said in a recent Xinhua interview that postal
services have many crucial resources that are invaluable in these
times of information technology.
</P>
<P>
Brennan, who was attending the 22nd Universal Postal Congress (
UPC) being held here from August 23 to September 15, spoke at the
general debate of the congress.
</P>
<P>
He said that almost everyone is a customer of post offices
which have the most extensive home delivery network in the world.
The reliability that the post has makes it the ideal trusted third
party for doing business on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
According to Anderson Consulting estimates, the value of on-
line shopping will grow to 180 billion U.S. dollars worldwide by
2003.
</P>
<P>
Although some traditional postal services are disappearing in
the face of the competition from electronic communications, new
value-added services as call centers, on-line shopping, supply
chain management and postal finances will enable the postal
services to survive and compete, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Postal administrations should shift from thinking merely of
mail to thinking about all the other things they can do," he said.
</P>
<P>
Post offices in some North American and European countries have
already started transforming their services. For example, the
Dutch post office has bought its way into the logistic industry by
acquiring TNT, a major international transport company; and the
Canadian post has offered electronic bill payment services to all
residents in the country.
</P>
<P>
Brennan said that for developing countries, the majority of the
members of the Universal Postal Union (UPU), the priority for
postal development should be coordinating their resources in a bid
to achieve the highest possible efficiency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
