<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moore Takes Office as WTO Director-General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Mike Moore of New Zealand
officially took office as the new Director-General of the World
Trade Organization (WTO) here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He and Supachai Panitchpakdi of Thailand were chosen as the WTO
's next two consecutive leaders by the ruling General Council on
July 22.
</P>
<P>
Moore will head the WTO until August 31, 2002 when he will be
replaced by Supachai who will also serve a three-year term of
office until August 31, 2005.
</P>
<P>
At the decision-making meeting on July 22, WTO members agreed
that neither should be eligible for reappointment as WTO director-
general, nor should his period of office be extended.
</P>
<P>
Normally, the term of office of the WTO chief is four years as
the former WTO Director-General Renato Ruggiero has served.
</P>
<P>
The decision was a compromise based on proposals by Bangladesh
and Australia after a year-long dispute among WTO members on who
would succeed Ruggiero. Ruggiero left office as scheduled on April
30, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
