<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian PM Leaves for Three-Nation Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Prime Minister
Hun Sen left here Wednesday for his three-nation trip to Canada,
Cuba and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Upon his departure at the airport, Hun Sen told reporters that
he has many things to talk with U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
during his stay in New York. He mentioned the issue of the
establishment of a Khmer Rouge tribunal with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. legal team, which is also leaving here Wednesday, held
two rounds of meetings with its Cambodian counterpart chaired by
Sok An, senior minister and minister of the Council of Ministers,
on the setting up of a mixed Khmer Rouge tribunal, but failed to
reach any agreement.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have wide divergence on the nature, structure and
composition of the tribunal, according to the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Om Yentieng, a top political affairs advisor to Prime Minister
Hun Sen, told reporters that the Cambodian government will not
change its positions on the Khmer Rouge tribunal.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen will lead a delegation of the royal government of
Cambodia to attend the Eighth Summit of the heads of state and
government of Francophone countries to be held in Canada from
September 3 to 5 at the invitation of his Canadian counterpart,
Jean Chretien.
</P>
<P>
After the visit to Canada, Hun Sen will pay an official visit
to Cuba from September 7 to 9, after which he will go to New York
to attend the 54th U.N. General Assembly and deliver a speech.
</P>
</TEXT>
