<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Lowers Prices of Gasoline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has announced to lower
gasoline prices by 200 Lebanese pounds (about 0.13 U.S. dollars)
per 20 liters, the first drop following three hikes since April.
</P>
<P>
In response to a fall in the international oil price, Lebanese
Oil Minister Suleiman Traboulsi Tuesday decreed that a 20-liter
tank of 92 octane gasoline, the lowest grade available at the
pump station, would cost 12,700 pounds (about 8.46 dollars), while
a tank of 98 octane gasoline would be priced at 13,000 pounds
(about 8.66 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The price of every 20 liters of undeaded gasoline is also
lowered to 13,000 pounds (about 8.66 dollars), but keeping
kerosene at 6,600 pounds (about 4.4 dollars) and increasing the
cost of fuel oil by 100 pounds (about 0.06 dollars) to 6,100
pounds (about 4.06 dollars), the Daily Star reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The head of the country's Association of Gas Station Owners,
Sami Brax, welcomed the move, saying "it would enhance sales,
although to a limited extent."
</P>
<P>
"The gas stations that stored large amounts of gasoline in
anticipation of another increase will lose, but not much," he told
the paper.
</P>
<P>
Last month, gasoline prices were initially raised by 400 pounds
(about 0.26 dollars) and then additional 300 pounds (about 0.2
dollars).
</P>
<P>
In April, the cabinet raised gasoline taxes by 2,000 pounds
(about 1.33 dollars) per 20 liters to bolster the government's
coffers.
</P>
<P>
Traboulsi said the previous hikes were necessary to offset
increases in international oil prices.
</P>
<P>
But, his decisions sparked criticism from taxi drivers, who
have demanded official permission to use diesel to lower costs and
combat competition from mini-buses and vans that have been
licensed in recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
