<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TB, HIV Threatens More than Health in S. Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, Sept. 1 (Xinhua) -- The deadly duo of tuberculosis
(TB) and Human Immunodeficiency virus (HIV) are threatening not
only health of the South Asians but also their economic
development and social integrity, The Rising Nepal quoted experts
as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Experts attending The Status and Trends of HIV/AIDS and TB in
SAARC Member Countries here Tuesday concurred that the HIV and TB
infections were already large and there was possibility of further
rise in the near future.
</P>
<P>
"Together they present a huge financial and social burden to
our member countries," the experts cautioned.
</P>
<P>
With three million TB deaths annually, World Health
Organization (WHO) has already declared TB as global emergency.
</P>
<P>
However, the burden of this disease in the South Asia is more
prevalent than in any other regions. Statistics reveal that 40
percent of the global burden of TB is concentrated in the region
while one third of annual global deaths from TB occur in this
region alone.
</P>
<P>
The health threat posed by HIV is equally high and equally
dangerous. By the end of 1998, the United Nations Program on
HIV/AIDS and WHO estimated that the number of people living with
HIV will have swollen up to 33.4 million globally, which is 10
percent higher than just a year ago.
</P>
<P>
More than 95 percent of the people with HIV live in the
developing countries and 95 percent of deaths caused by the
infection occurred in these countries.
</P>
<P>
In order to mitigate the effect of the deadly duo, Deputy
Director of SAARC TB Center Dr. Kumar suggested that a dual
strategy be formulated to fight the dual epidemic. He further
suggested that mobilizing communities, unifying national and
international efforts and formulating regional strategy and
national specific action plans for the South Asian countries would
help prevent and control TB and HIV infections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Employment Up 4.3 Percent in July in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines posted an
employment increase of 4.3 percent to 29.1 million persons in July
1999 from 27.9 million a year earlier, an official statement said
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The employment increase almost matches the nation's increased
labor force in July this year, which amounted to 1.12 million
persons, according to the statement released by the National
Statistics Office.
</P>
<P>
Of the newly-increased employment, the agriculture sector
registered 800,000 persons, 6.8 percent up from July 1998.
</P>
<P>
Employment in services recorded an increase of 434,000, or 3.5
percent up, while the industrial sector slightly increased by
13,000, or 0.3 percent up from July 1998.
</P>
<P>
The total number of Filipinos aged 15 years old and over
reached 48.3 million in July, of which 31.7 million joined the
labor force in the month, up 3.7 percent from July 1998.
</P>
<P>
Those who were not in the labor force, like housewives,
students, disabled and retired persons, increased by 98,000 to
16.6 million in July 1999 from 16.5 million a year earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
