<HEADLINE> U.S. Government Promises to Help California Fight Wildfires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Agriculture Secretary
Dan Glickman assured California firefighters "they will have the
resources they need" as he toured the worst-burned area in the
state Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"There is not a budget cap on firefighting," said Glickman. "
When it comes to natural disasters, the government does respond,
and Congress does respond, the president does respond."
</P>
<P>
Fires across California have scorched more than 130,000 acres,
exhausted the state's firefighting resources and forced
evacuations of residents, hikers, campers and vacationers in some
of the most severe areas.
</P>
<P>
The worst fire in U.S. West has been one near Lake Arrowhead in
the Apple Valley, 75 miles (120 kilometers) east of Los Angeles,
that has scorched nearly 50,000 acres of brush and pine forest.
</P>
<P>
"This is the No. 1 priority fire -- given the size and location
of it," said Glickman who visited the site in responses to state
pleas for disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
California Governor Gray Davis Friday asked President Clinton
to declare a federal emergency for four counties in the state. A
federal emergency would allow California to receive more
assistance from federal agencies, including the Defense Department
and U.S. Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
California is not the only state fighting uncontrolled blazes.
Flames are raging in Idaho, Montana and Utah Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
