<HEADLINE> China's First Arctic Expedition Lays Foundation for Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The 56-day North Pole
expedition, China's first government-sponsored Arctic expedition,
has laid a sound foundation for further polar research, said the
chief scientist aboard the homeward-bound expedition ship Snow
Dragon today.
</P>
<P>
Chief Scientist Chen Liqi told Xinhua that the expedition
achieved reliable and valuable research data, laying a sound
foundation for future research.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese scientists will offer a large amount of first-hand
data and many new scientific views to international polar
researchers," said Chen, who has been to the South Pole and North
Pole many times.
</P>
<P>
Chen, also director of the Polar Research Office under the
State Oceanic Administration, said that the expedition has greatly
improved the Chinese scientists' ability to conduct research in
the polar region and will promote this endeavor in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
"I hope some of the young scientists who took part in the
expedition can become leading world scientists in the coming
decades," he said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 54 scientists and technicians, with an average age
of 40.7, participated in the expedition.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation between Chinese and foreign scientists also was
increased and strengthened by this expedition, Chen noted, saying
that polar research needs more support from the international
academic community, and that international cooperation should be
expanded for the further study of global climate changes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
