<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Huangpu River to Become Tourist Attraction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
city, has unveiled a massive program to turn its Huangpu River
into a tourist attraction comparable to Hong Kong's Victoria
Harbor and Australia's Sydney Harbor in the coming century.
</P>
<P>
An official with the local municipal government said that all
coal, chemical, and bulk cargo docks in the downtown area will be
moved to a new port area on the outskirts of Shanghai, and tourist,
recreational, and commercial facilities will be built instead
along the river.
</P>
<P>
Among the major projects is a 10,000-sq-m recreational center
in the southern part of the Bund along Shanghai's waterfront.
</P>
<P>
The Huangpu River, which flows into the Yangtze River, has been
a transportation channel for more than 100 years. But in recent
years, the amount of cargo handled by the city's wharves in the
urban area has been declining and has had a negative effect on the
urban environment.
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade, the municipality has built a series of
scenic spots along the river, including the Orient Pearl TV Tower
and the picturesque Binjiang Avenue, while giving a facelift to
the famous Bund.
</P>
<P>
This autumn, a dragon boat competition, the first of its kind
in Shanghai, will be held on the river as part of the city's
effort to promote tourism.
</P>
<P>
These plans have drawn an increasing number of overseas
investors, and dozens have shown their keen interest in investing
in the city.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
