<HEADLINE> Interview: Chinese President's Visit to Further Boost Ties With Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
John Howard said Chinese President Jiang Zemin's forthcoming
state visit to Australia will significantly advance bilateral ties
in a recent interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Howard described the visit as "a very very significant event"
and "a huge boost to the relationship between Australia and China.
"
</P>
<P>
"We are looking forward very much to welcoming President Jiang
Zemin," he said, adding that Jiang's visit, the first ever by a
Chinese head of state, will be an opportunity for them to discuss
important bilateral and international issues.
</P>
<P>
Howard predicted that the visit will be "very successful."
</P>
<P>
Describing the bilateral relations as "very sound and strong,"
Howard said that since his summit meeting with Jiang in Beijing in
1997, exchanges of visit of ministers between the two countries
have been conducted and a very good dialog on defense and regional
issues has been developed.
</P>
<P>
While Australian companies are very active investors in China
in resources, manufacture and services, China is a valued investor
in Australia, Howard said.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries reached 10 billion Australian
dollars (6.6 billion U.S. dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
On Australia's China policy, Howard said there are a number of
reasons that Australia gives one of its foreign policy priorities
to China.
</P>
<P>
In its 1997 White Paper on Foreign Affairs and Trade, Australia
identified China as one of the four countries which Australia has
key relations with.
</P>
<P>
China is a big and influential country by any measurement, he
said, and it is important for a country like Australia, which is a
medium power, to develop relations with China.
</P>
<P>
"And of course, there are big areas of cooperation," he said,
adding that the two countries should "maximize the areas of mutual
interest."
</P>
<P>
"China is a very big and very influential country and all the
nations in the region can build constructive relations with China,
and then China can contribute a great deal to the whole region, to
the stability and wealth of the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Howard, who called for an engagement China policy of the
Clinton administration during his U.S. trip last July, said he
believed that the word "containment" is an "old expression" and "
engagement looks to the future."
</P>
<P>
In the interview, Howard also reaffirmed Australia's "One China
" policy and its support for China's membership in the World Trade
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
He said his country has been supporting "One China" policy for
a long time and will stick to it.
</P>
<P>
As for China's WTO membership, Howard said, "We want to see
China in the World Trade Organization. We have already reached an
understanding with China."
</P>
<P>
"If China becomes a member of the World Trade Organization,
that will obviously improve trade between our two countries," he
said. "But that's not just bilateral benefit. It's a very big
group benefit in China being part of the World Trade Organization.
" 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
