<HEADLINE> Clark: Work in Balkans Not Over Despite Progress in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Wesley Clark, supreme
European allied commander of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), said Tuesday that violence against the Serbs
in Kosovo is going down, but the work in the Balkans is not over.
</P>
<P>
"The instance of violence has gone down dramatically over the
last couple of weeks," he said in a speech at the American
Enterprise Institute on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic Albanians started an ethnic cleansing campaign
against the Serbs in the Yugoslav province after Serb forces
withdrew and NATO troops controlled the province. Thousands of
Serbs fled their homes.
</P>
<P>
Belgrade has protested against the uncompliance by the Kosovo
Liberation Army (KLA) with its commitment to be disarmed in
accordance with the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
But Clark claimed that the KLA is complying with the agreement.
"The compliance by the KLA with their promises that they undertook
to KFOR and NATO has been, by and large, satisfactory at the 60-
day point," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We're looking ahead anxiously to the 90-day point for the
completion of the demilitarization program. But that seems to be
very much on track. There's a great deal of work to do to build
the institutions there, to assure we do have a climate of security,
and to move into the next steps," he said.
</P>
<P>
The American interests, the general said, are at risk in the
Balkans. "Europe will remain a dynamic environment, and the
Balkans will remain a crucible for testing of our own values and
capabilities."
</P>
<P>
"I know the Balkans is on the -- at least what we would
consider to be the geographic periphery of Europe. But it is at
the strategic center of Europe today ... And at that strategic
center, America indeed has its vital interests engaged," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to NATO's future, Clark said the organization's
credibility "has been enhanced."
</P>
<P>
In Washington, the alliance outlined its new strategic concept
to interfere in conflicts beyond borders of its members.
</P>
<P>
"It was a concept that we spent a long time debating
theoretically, but we already took the first practical steps in
the air campaign and in subsequent operations to deliver on the
theory of that strategic concept," Clark said.
</P>
<P>
Russia, which strongly opposed NATO's air campaign against
Yugoslavia, will no doubt remain active in pursuit of its own
interests, Clark said, but adding that "hopefully" it will remain
a partner with NATO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
