<HEADLINE> Denmark Announces Efforts to Reduce National Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Danish government on
Tuesday announced its draft state budget for 2000, with the target
of reducing national debts as the top priority.
</P>
<P>
Denmark will continue a tight fiscal policy next year. The
draft plan shows the country's 2000 budget will have a surplus of
7.9 billion kroner (around 1 billion U.S. dollars) and will slash
the national debts to 44.4 percent of the gross domestic product (
GDP).
</P>
<P>
The government said the national debts have to be cut in order
to make up for the increasing expense on pension for more and more
aged people.
</P>
<P>
Denmark has pursued a tight fiscal policy for more than a
decade. The national debts have been reducing year by year, and
expenditure on the interests of the debts dropped from 7.3 percent
of the total GDP in 1985 to 3.8 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The draft plan shows the largest expense of the Danish
government will be on unemployment relief.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
