<HEADLINE> Brazil Announces Development Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso on Tuesday announced an economic recovery plan
that envisaged an annual growth of four percent in the coming four
years.
</P>
<P>
The plan "Brazil in Progress", with a total outlay of some 600
billion U.S. dollars, is aimed to build a strong, just,
competitive and better country for Brazilians, said President
Cardoso in the Planalto Palace.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, Brazil will spent 134.167 billion
dollars in the year 2000, 148.091 billion dollars in 2001, 156.037
billion dollars in 2002 and 161.865 billion dollars in 2003.
</P>
<P>
The largest Latin American country will create 8.5 million new
jobs in the four years, reducing the jobless rate by 1.5
percentage points. Brazil's unemployment rate in July was 7.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
The "Brazil in Progress" plan has a basket of 358 programs
designed to meet the basic needs of the Brazilian people,
including health, education, security, accommodation and
transportation, said Cardoso.
</P>
<P>
"Brazil in Progress" is the second plan presented by President
Cardoso in his second term. The first plan "Brazil in Action",
which started to be implemented in August, 1996, focused on
construction efforts.
</P>
<P>
The second plan, along with the draft budget of the federal
government for the year 2000, will soon be presented to Congress
for approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
