<HEADLINE> U.S. Congressmen Visit Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Two Democratic members of the U.S.
Congress are continuing their visits to Cuba as the heads of two
different missions.
</P>
<P>
Dannice Davis, from Illinois, and Tom Lampson, from Texas,
arrived in Cuba on Sunday. They have begun contacts separately
with the local authorities as part of their stay which would last
till the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
Davis, accompanied by a group of doctors, visited hospitals in
the capital city and the Latin American School of Medical Science.
He has planned a meeting with the officials of the Commission of
Health, Sport and Environment of the National Assembly (Parliament)
.
</P>
<P>
Lampson, for his part, visited agricultural cooperatives
together with a party of North American agriculturists. His
working agenda includes meetings with the officials of the
Ministries of Agriculture and Foreign Trade.
</P>
<P>
A third delegation, led by Democratic representative Sanford
Bishop from Georgia, will join the two men tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
A government source said that the three delegations will meet
with National Assembly President Ricardo Alarcon on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the same source, Bishop showed interest in
possible official cooperation in anti-drug operations between Cuba
and the U.S. For this reason he will hold discussions with the
officials of the Cuban institutions responsible for the fight
against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
To explore the possibility of real bilateral cooperation in
this matter, Democrats Tomas Daschle and Byron Dorgan paid a visit
to Cuba in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
The two Democrats had talks with Cuban President Fidel Castro,
Justice Minister and President of the National Anti-drug
Commission Roberto Dias Sotolongo and Economy Minister Jose Luis
Rodriguez. 
</P>
</TEXT>
