<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace March of 1 Million Proposed in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A world renowned Sri Lankan
social activist has proposed a march of 1 million people from the
south to the war-torn north this month to press for an end to the
prolonged ethnic conflict of the country.
</P>
<P>
The march will be led by A.T. Ariyaratne who heads Sarvodaya
(All People's Prosperous Movement), a 41-year-old nongovernmental
organization that carries out social work mainly in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The official Daily News Wednesday quoted Ariyaratne as saying
that once initial arrangements have been completed a date will be
fixed for the march.
</P>
<P>
The march will start from five different points in the country
and end in the rebel-controlled north, about 260 kilometers from
Colombo, said Ariyaratne.
</P>
<P>
The route will pass both military and Tamil rebels' camps and
through Sinhala, Muslim and Tamil villages.
</P>
<P>
In the course of the march participants will spread the message
of peace while encouraging bystanders to join in.
</P>
<P>
Ariyaratne said though their target is a million participants
he expects the number be doubled.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday over 200,000 people participated in a peace march
and meditation campaign organized by Sarvodaya in Colombo when
only 100,000 were expected, said Ariyaratne, adding that this
clearly reflected the people's desire for peace.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has been plagued by a 16-year-old civil war between
the Sinhalese majority-controlled government and the Tamil
minority rebels who demand a separate homeland in the north and
east of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
