<HEADLINE> Thirteen Delegations Take Part in Indonesia Open Badminton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Around 250 players from 13
countries and regions are set to compete Wednesday in the
Indonesia Open in Denpasar, about 1,000 kilometers east of here,
according to a release quoted by the Indonesian Observer.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia and Denmark, two of the world's badminton powers,
look set for stiff rivalry in the tournament which runs until
September 5 and offers a total prize of 150,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the men's singles, 13 of the world's 20 top players,
including Singaporean Open champion Heriyanto Arbi, are ready to
take up the challenge.
</P>
<P>
Local hopefuls include Budi Santoso (world's number six),
Hendrawan (number seven), Taufik Hidayat (number nine) and Rony
Agustinus 16).
</P>
<P>
Denmark will deploy world number two Peter Gade-Christensen,
the 1999 All-England champion Poul Erik Hoyer-Larsen, Peter
Rasmussen and Keneth Johanssen.
</P>
<P>
Rashid Sidek, Wong Choong Han and Roslin Hashim will spearhead
the Malaysian squad while Sweden will hang their hopes on Thomas
Johansson.
</P>
<P>
The absence of reigning champion Mia Audina should leave
Camilla Martin from Denmark favorite to win the women's singles
title. Mia now plays for the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Martin is likely to face a tough challenge from fellow Dane
Mette Sorenson, runner-up last year.
</P>
<P>
Cindana Hartono and Lidya Djaelawijaya from Indonesia will have
to prove that they can do the job without Mia, who used to be the
country's number one player.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia look to maintain supremacy in the men's doubles with
Toni Gunawan/Chandra Wijaya, Flandy Limpele/Wahyu Agung, Ricky
Subagja/Rexy Mainaky and Antonius/Halim Heryanto in the running.
</P>
<P>
In the women's doubles, the Indonesian pair of Etty Tanri and
Cynthia Tuwanakota are seeded second behind Ann Jorgenson/Vange
Maiken from Denmark.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Elysa and Deyana Lomban from Indonesia will
have to retain their titles. However, Elysa and Deyana will have
to work hard to overcome Danish pairs of Mette Schjoldager and Ann-
Lou Jorgensen in the quarterfinals. If they reach the semifinals,
they will likely challenge top seeded Ann Jorgensen and Vange
Maiken.
</P>
<P>
In the mixed doubles, Dane Michael Sogaard was optimistic that
he and partner Rikki Olsen would make a comeback after beating Tri
Kusherjanto and Minarti Timur from Indonesia. Last year in Jakarta,
Sogaard and Olsen had to bow out to Tri and Minarti.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Badminton Association of Indonesia (PBSI) deputy
athletes development officer Hadi Hazri Tuesday expressed hope
that Indonesian shuttlers in the women's singles and doubles and
mixed doubles could take advantage of the absence of Chinese and
South Korean players in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
"If we see from their drawings, our national players could
benefit. They must not lose in early rounds before their own
public. With the recent point system where athletes will get a
point bonus if they can beat seeded players, I hope our shuttlers
will not be afraid and can win. They must think of it as their
chance," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hadi said PBSI plans to petition the International Badminton
Federation (IBF) to take steps on certain countries' absences in
the Indonesia Open.
</P>
<P>
He said he would also ask PBSI chief of foreign affairs to urge
the IBF to warning the countries.
</P>
<P>
China skipped the Indonesia Open for the third time since 1997.
South Korea also missed the tournament for the second time due to
financial restraints in sending its players here.
</P>
<P>
Hadi said PBSI would also request the Asian Badminton
Confederation (ABC) urge other Asian countries to compete in
tournaments in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We regret that Asian countries don't support tournaments
staged in the same region. I hope the ABC will take steps to
overcome the problem," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
