<HEADLINE> New Bridges, Roads Ease Traffic in Urumqi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Traffic is flowing more
smoothly in Urumqi these days now that a number of new river
bridges and highway overpasses have been added to the frontier
city's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
In 1984, this capital of northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region had just five bridges spanning the Urumqi River.
Now, there are 70, clearing the way for more people arriving from
the countryside to live on both sides of the river.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 33 elevated overpasses have been built over the
city streets.
</P>
<P>
These structures have added to the appeal of the far west city,
which covers 140 sq km and has 1.55 million residents.
</P>
<P>
Half a century ago, the city was divided into two parts by the
Urumqi River. When the People's Republic of China was founded in
1949, there were only three wooden bridges across the river.
</P>
<P>
Now, 14 more overpasses are being built over Xihong and
Qiantangjiang roads and other congested thoroughfares.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, Urumqi has spent 16.3 billion yuan on
infrastructure development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
