<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Technology Is Crucial for Beijing Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- "The development of high and
new technology is crucial for Beijing's economy," said Jia Qinglin,
secretary of the Beijing Municipal Committee of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
When asked how Beijing will face the challenge of the 21st
century, Jia said that Beijing will attach great importance to
technological development, and it will play a crucial role in
social development as outlined in both Deng Xiaoping Theory and at
the 15th CPC National Congress.
</P>
<P>
China has made rapid progress in technology and science over
the past 50 years since the founding of New China in 1949,
especially during the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
There are now more than 500 city-level scientific institutions,
50 key national laboratories, and 26 national engineering research
centers in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Beijing also boasts some 1.1 million technicians and
professionals, 327 academicians with the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, and 162 academicians with the Chinese Academy of
Engineering now working in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the gross domestic product had been growing at an
average annual rate of 9.8 percent from 1978 to 1998, and
technology and science have contributed to 51 percent of national
economic growth of the city.
</P>
<P>
Jia said that competition among nations is actually a
technological contest, which is both a challenge and an
opportunity. Therefore, Beijing will make every effort to further
the development of science and technology and industrialize the
fruits of scientific research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
