<HEADLINE> Cuban Economy to Recover: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Cuba's gross domestic product
grew 6 percent in the first six months of the year, indicating a
quick economic recovery, said Vice-minister of Economy and
Planning Alfonso Casanova on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure showed that Cuba is going to overfulfil its plans
for 1999, which was a growth of 2.5 percent, said Casanova at a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said this was the result of the changes in the principal
sectors of the national economy, especially in the sugar industry
which has witnessed a moderate recovery.
</P>
<P>
The production of sugar, the major catalyst for the economy of
the island country, grew by almost half a million tons in the last
harvest, after a fall to a record low of 3.2 million tons in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister said that the recovery of the sugar industry
has had a positive impact on the economy of the country, as well
as on tourism, which has recorded a growth of over 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Industry registered a notable growth of 5 percent over the
first half of the year, agriculture 6 percent and construction 7
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Casanova also mentioned a rise in productive efficiency,
because of a better relationship between energy consumption and
production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
