<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Synthetic Oral Insulin Created in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 31 (Xinhua) -- After decades of research,
Mexican scientists recently created a synthetic insulin for
diabetics to take by mouth, according to the local press.
</P>
<P>
With pharmacological properties identical to natural insulin,
the synthetic insulin is said to be able to adequately control the
sugar level in the organism and avoid complications usually caused
by insulin injection, such as sight problems, skin allergies and
complications with the nervous system.
</P>
<P>
Experiments conducted on laboratory mice showed that the
synthetic insulin is capable of reducing the glucose level by 40
percent in a short period of time, according to the scientists
from the National Autonomous University of Mexico, who began the
research project in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the purified animal insulin, the synthetic one will not
be deactivated by enzymes in the intestine, nor does it produce
anti-bodies, the scientists said.
</P>
<P>
Miguel Gutierrez, a chemical engineer heading the research team,
said that after being absorbed by the intestine, the synthetic
insulin is distributed rapidly into the organism by the peripheral
tissues and immediately begins its therapeutic action.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
