<HEADLINE> Sampras Withdraws, Sixth seed Henman Upset at U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- In the wake of the stunning
withdrawal of top seed Pete Sampras, Patrick Rafter of Australia
and American Lindsay Davenport start their bids to repeat as U.S.
Open champions today when they play their first round matches at
the 14.5 million US dollars Grand Slam event in New York.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who was seeking his record 13th Grand Slam title and
fifth U.S. Open championship, had withdrawn because of a strain in
his lower back.
</P>
<P>
Sampras sustained the injury during a practice session with
Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil on Sunday. Sampras had been the hottest
player on the men's tour, winning Wimbledon for the sixth time and
taking 24 consecutive matches and four titles before withdrawing
with a hip injury during a match against fellow Amercian Vincent
Spadea two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Sampra's injury was diagnosed as a small herniated disc. He is
expected to be out of the Pilot Pen in New Haven, Connecticut,
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, sixth-seeded Tim Henman of Britain became the first
men's upset victim at the U.S. Open tennis championships when he
was beaten by unseeded Argentine Guillermo Canas in straight sets
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Henman who ranked fifth in the world, was unable to return the
strong volleys from the 21-year-old Argentina who only ranked 68th
and suffered a defeat 7-6 (7-1), 6-4, 6-3 on Louis Armstrong
Stadium court.
</P>
<P>
Henman, who reached the round of 16 in last year's Open, had
beaten Canas in three sets in their only previous encounter in the
second round of last year's Canadian Open.
</P>
<P>
Five other seeded men's players are in action today. Kuerten,
who is seeded fifth, plays Bohdan Ulihrach of the Czech Republic,
No. 7 Todd Martin of the United States avoided a five-set meltdown
and held off Stephane Huet of France 6-4, 6-3, 6-7 (2-7), 6-7 (5-7)
,7-6 (7-3) in a four hour match.
</P>
<P>
The 13th seeded Alex Corretja of Spain goes against hard-
serving Australian Wayne Arthurs and No. 16 Nicolas Kiefer of
Germany faces Jason Stoltenberg of Australia.
</P>
<P>
Seles, a nine-time Grand Slam champion, missed a month of
action with an arm injury before reaching the final at last week's
du Maurier Open in Montreal, but she was denied a fifth straight
title at the event by Martina Hingis of Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
No. 9 Julie Halard-Decugis of France defeated Cara Black of
Zimbabwe 6-3, 5-7, 6-3. 
</P>
