<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Several Million People Out of Poverty in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Seven million rural people
have been lifted out of poverty since 1990 in central China's
Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the number of the needy had
decreased to 3.16 million in 1998 from 10.4 million in 1990.
</P>
<P>
During the eight years, local treasury departments at all
levels have earmarked a total of 3.475 billion yuan for their
poverty-relief efforts, and last year alone they allocated 646
million yuan for poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
In addition, local treasury departments also implemented a set
of fiscal preferential policies to assist the 34 poorest counties
in the province so that the impoverished could improve their
ability to develop.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Henan Province has begun to place more
emphasis on infrastructure construction, improving production
conditions, and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
For these purposes, 899 million yuan was put into some poor
regions in 1997 and 1998, 83.5 percent of the total fund.
</P>
<P>
With the fund, local governments have created 49 small and
medium-sized reservoirs and maintained and rebuilt 29 water-power
stations and 3,220 drinking-water projects. They also built or
reconstructed 3,132 kilometers of road and 807 bridges and
culverts.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 466 schools, 148 village clinics, and seven
country broadcasting stations were also established during this
period.
</P>
<P>
Due to the improvement in production conditions and
infrastructure, the economy and social facilities of the poor
counties have greatly developed.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last year, the government revenue of the 34
poorest counties in Henan Province had reached 2.382 billion yuan,
nearly double that of 1990.
</P>
<P>
The per capita income of the farmers in the poor counties had
risen to 1,579.22 yuan in 1998 from only 326 yuan in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Also, many roads in most villages are now open to traffic, and
telephones have been installed in households across the province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
