<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Y2K Bug: Is Asia Prepared? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- With just four months to go
before the clock ticks over to 2000, is Asia prepared to withstand
the Y2k bug that many fear could trigger havoc?
</P>
<P>
There remains no definite answer to this question, because
while Asian countries are working hard to meet the deadline, there
is still much work to be done before the region is
"Y2K-compliant."
</P>
<P>
The Y2k bug is a built-in flaw in older computer systems that
prevent them from correctly recognizing dates from January 1, 2000
onward.
</P>
<P>
As a result, such computer systems could mistake the year 2000
for the 1900 and could possibly jeopardize operation of computer
dependent industries.
</P>
<P>
However, according to a recent survey by the Gartner Group, a
consultancy, progress in the region on moves against the Y2K bug
is uneven. Singapore, South Korea and Japan have received top
rating, but much work remains to be down in many other Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
Because of the inadequate preparations So far, Asian government
officials are expressing cautious optimism. They said that crucial
services in the region are not expected to be in chaos when 2000
comes, but problems such as temporary power shortages or
telecommunication breakdowns may not be completely avoided.
</P>
<P>
"The chance of things like a collapse in infrastructure -- like
electricity, gas, water, communications -- on January 1, 2000, or
Y2K issues making any noticeable impact on the nation's gross
domestic product, is very unlikely," said Takeo Shina, head of
Japan's advisory panel on millennium compliance.
</P>
<P>
Amable Aguiluz, chairman of the Philippine Presidential
Commission on year 2000 compliance, said that most of the seven
mission-critical sectors in his country are at least 70 percent
Y2K prepared except the health care sector which is at 69 percent.
</P>
<P>
The other six critical sectors are utilities, finance,
tele-communication, transportation, manufacturing and government.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the millennium bug is no more than a passing
storm. but, nonetheless, we should be prepared," Aguiluz said at a
recent meeting.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, the deadline for banking full compliance is
June 30, 1999 and for all other sectors is September 30, 1999. So
far, most financial institutions in the country have already
conducted Y2K Simulation tests and been proved Y2K compliant.
</P>
<P>
Just like the Philippines, other Asian countries and business
organizations are taking the 2YK bug seriously.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that China has spent 5 billion yuan (600 million
U.S. dollars) to ensure trading and banking system will not crash.
In Japan, Japan Airlines has spent 25 million U.S. dollars combing
31 million lines of computer code to ensure its jets keep flying
unevenfully.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, while many countries have made rapid progress
plugging the gaps in crucial systems, the region is "a little bit
behind, firstly in terms of awareness, and secondly in terms of
doing anything about the bug," said Stephen Kucia, managing
director of an American company that has carried out Y2K work in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
In some countries, preparations have been hampered by a lack of
funds and inadequate coordination.
</P>
<P>
Experts also warned that without full preparations in the
region, the Y2K bug will not only hit individual countries
themselves, but their trading partners because of their
inter-dependence.
</P>
<P>
"If there are problems in Hong Kong, they would probably come
externally, from our international trading partners," said Roy Ko,
head consultant of Hong Kong's Productivity Council, which
overseas Y2K readiness of some 300,000 local small and
medium-sized firms.
</P>
<P>
Facing the potential challenges, some Asian countries are
preparing for the worst on Y2K bug. In the Philippines, the
central bank is directing all banks to prepare for the worst-case
scenario in drafting their Y2K plans.
</P>
<P>
As the country's health sector is only 69 percent Y2K prepared,
the government is encouraging state and private hospitals to pool
their resources together to tackle the bug. At the same time, It
asked hospitals that are non-Y2K compliant to direct patients to
those that are already compliant.
</P>
<P>
Some of Japan's biggest manufacturers, such as electronics
giant NEC Corp. and audio equipment maker Aiwa Co. Ltd, said last
month that they are building up extra stockpiles of necessary
components in anticipation of problems related to the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
With the year 2000 approaching, government officials and
experts are appealing to less-prepared sectors or organizations
for quicker steps against the Y2K bug.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
