<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Chinese Breeder 's Dream (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Editor's note: This year marks the 50th anniversary of the
founding of the People' s Republic of China. Xinhua News Agency is
releasing about 50 stories on Chinese men and women, young and old,
illustrating the changes that have taken place in China over the
past half century. These people will describe their own
experiences and how they fit into the changes in the motherland.
This is the eleventh story.
</P>
<P>
JINAN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- "I have a dream, in which
farmland will be able to produce a higher grain yield," said Li
Denghai, 50, president of the Laizhou Academy of Agricultural
Sciences of east China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to make his dream come true, Li has in the past
34 years set up a world record of maize yield per hectare of some
16.44 tons, adding over 40 million tons to the nation's grain
output by extending his high-yield maize seeds in 47 million
hectares.
</P>
<P>
He was depressed in 1966 after observing that the yield per
hectare in China was only 1.5 tons to the 2.25 tons when he
graduated from junior high school at 17.
</P>
<P>
It was then that he made up his mind to become involved in
breeding research projects aimed at increasing the maize yield and
help his hometown villagers eliminate poverty as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
He spent whole days in the fields and studied theories on
breeding late into the night until he went to the Laizhou Academy
of Agricultural Sciences in 1972.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the maize yield per hectare in the U.S. was
already 18.75 tons in his graduation year had an extremely big
impact on him.
</P>
<P>
He wrote down in his diary on his graduation day: "I will
devote my whole life to the research of corn breeding and to
realize a great farming dream."
</P>
<P>
Some westerners had predicted when New China was founded in
1949 that the country would not be able to solve the problem of
grain shortage on its own.
</P>
<P>
However, half a century of hard work has proved that China has
been able to provide for 22 percent of the world's population with
some 10 percent of the world's arable land, realizing a balance
between demand and supply on grain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990901.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
