<HEADLINE> China Starts Y2k Testing of Power Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A nationwide year 2000(Y2k)
testing was carried out on August 31 in China's power system to
verify whether all the power system-related computers were Y2k
compliant, today's China Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Economic and Trade Commission, the joint
testing started at 10 p.m.yesterday and will last till 1 a.m. on
September 10.
</P>
<P>
It is scheduled to cover 29 municipalities, provinces and
autonomous regions. The State Power Corporation of China (SPCC) is
in charge during the testing process.
</P>
<P>
Starting in August, 1998, all regional power system was urged
to carry out detection and upgrade work to be Y2k compliant.
</P>
<P>
"Regional and separated testing has just finished in mid-August,
" said Jiao Baoli, from the SPCC.
</P>
<P>
According to SPCC, the testing will fall on the automatic
system in different areas including SPCC's regulation center,
regulation center of regional grids, power transformation stations
and power telecommunication system.
</P>
<P>
Jiao also said that the testing is unlikely to affect the power
transmission systems in households and other small individual
users because all the emergency measures are in place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
