<HEADLINE> China Sets Good Example for Developing Countries: Yemeni Vice President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- China's great success achieved
with its reform and opening-up policy is attracting worldwide
attention and China has set a good example for other developing
countries, Yemeni Vice President Abdo Rabo Mansour Hadi said in a
recent interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"China has become one of the major economic powers in the world,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
"Many economic and technological development zones in China
have become centers of industrial production, advanced technology
research and foreign investment. They are the epitome of
achievements made by China's reform and opening-up policy," he
said.
</P>
<P>
In April, Hadi paid a week-long visit to China at the
invitation of his Chinese counterpart Hu Jintao. He said he was
deeply impressed by Shanghai and Shenzhen, models of China's
development.
</P>
<P>
On relations between Yemen and China, Hadi said, "Friendship
between us has borne fruits. The Yemeni people will never forget
the economic assistance and help from the Chinese government."
</P>
<P>
He noted that Sino-Yemeni ties have developed steadily since
the two countries established diplomatic ties in 1956. China
helped Yemen build its first highway, the Sana - Hudaydah highway,
which played a key role in its revolution and economic
construction. In addition, China sent more than 2,500 medical
workers to Yemen over the past three decades.
</P>
<P>
"President Ali Abdullah Saleh and I are very happy to notice
that the Chinese people anticipate great events this year," Hadi
said, referring to the 50th anniversary of the founding of the
People's Republic of China and return of Macao to the motherland.
"We share the happiness of the Chinese people and wish China to
accomplish the task of unifying the country as early as possible."
</P>
<P>
The 55-year old vice president was born in Yemen's southern
province of Abyan. He was appointed defense minister in May, 1995,
and became vice president in October the same year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
