<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, September 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Four foreign hostages and their Iranian guide
kidnapped in Iran's southeastern province of Kerman two weeks ago
were freed at 20:30 hours local time (1600 GMT).
</P>
<P>
According to the official Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA),
a provincial official said the released hostages would be united
with their family shortly. But no detail is given about the
release, or the condition of the hostages. (Iran-Hostages-Release)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Preliminary figures show that voter turnout
in East Timor Monday stood at 98.6 percent, a U.N. official said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ballot was organized and conducted by the United Nations to
determine the future of East Timor -- special autonomy within
Indonesia or transition to independence after 23 years of being
considered internationally as a non-self-governing territory. (UN-
East Timor-Ballot)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair ignored Protestant
anger Tuesday and backed his Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam
over her ruling that the Irish Republican Army's cease-fire was
intact.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with Mowlam, Blair, who was just
back from holiday, emphasized the government's commitment to the
peace process. (N.Ireland-Blair)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- The European Union (EU) can no longer put off the
question of Turkey's possible entrance into the continent-wide
union, said Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Talking with the financial daily Il Sole 24 Ore, Dini said the
EU will have to "recognize Turkey's right to bear the title of
candidate of the union" at its December meeting in Helsinki. (
Italy-Turkey-EU) 
</P>
