<HEADLINE> SADC Members Urged to Jointly Combat Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 31 (Xinhua) -- A leader of an African
non- governmental organization said Tuesday that the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) countries should co-operate
in fighting corruption.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Director for Human Rights and Documentation
Trust of Southern Africa, Philiat Matsheza, told a press
conference in Dar es Salaam that there is a need for SADC
countries to participate fully in the war against corruption,
because this part of Africa is heavily hit by the evil.
</P>
<P>
A four-day roundtable SADC conference on ethics and
anti-corruption will be opened in Dar es Salaam on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Matsheza said the roundtable conference will provide an
opportunity for 14-member SADC countries to co-operate more
closely in fighting the evil.
</P>
<P>
He said that delegates will make suggestions to leaders on what
should be done.
</P>
<P>
The director said that corruption is a complicated issue, which
a country sometimes feel difficult to deal with individually.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's Prevention of Corruption Bureau, said in a statement
that earlier this week that participants at the meeting will be
armed with specific and practical skills and strategies for
enhancing existing anti- corruption efforts in their countries.
</P>
<P>
The conference, the second of its kind, is co-hosted by the NGO
and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania was chosen as a venue of the second conference because
of its extensive experience and commitment to anti-corruption
activities.
</P>
<P>
The first roundtable conference was held in Mashatu, Botswana
in October 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
