<HEADLINE> Over 98 Percent of East Timorese Vote Monday: U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Preliminary figures show
that voter turnout in East Timor Monday stood at 98.6 percent, a
U.N. official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ballot was organized and conducted by the United Nations to
determine the future of East Timor -- special autonomy within
Indonesia or transition to independence after 23 years of being
considered internationally as a non-self-governing territory.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Spokesman for the U.N. Secretary-General Manoel de
Almeida e Silva said all ballot boxes "are safe and well" in the
central counting station in Dili, capital of the half-island
territory.
</P>
<P>
Counting will take a week before the result is announced, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Indonesia has committed to maintaining law
and order in East Timor which it has ruled since 1976 after the
withdrawal of Portugal.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. brokered an agreement on May 5 between Indonesia and
Portugal to hold the ballot and it will assist the peaceful
implementation of the ballot result.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council has increased the number of U.N.
military liaison officers in East Timor from 50 to 300 and the
international police from 280 to 460.
</P>
<P>
Under U.N. auspices, a 25-member East Timor interim
consultative commission was set up to bring political leaders from
pro- and anti-independence forces together for reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The commission held its first meeting Tuesday afternoon, the
spokesman confirmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
