<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Pledges Backing for Mowlam on N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
ignored Protestant anger Tuesday and backed his Northern Ireland
Secretary Mo Mowlam over her ruling that the Irish Republican
Army's ceasefire was intact.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with Mowlam, Blair, who was just
back from holiday, emphasized the government's commitment to the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
And he stressed that it was vital for the Northern Ireland
political parties to become fully engaged in the review of
Northern Ireland's stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Blair's office said earlier that former U.S. Senator George
Mitchell was ready to launch a review next Monday but would first
seek assurances from all parties that they remained committed to
it.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the Irish Republic hope Mitchell, who brokered last
year's Good Friday peace agreement for the British province, can
employ the review to end a long-running deadlock between
Protestant and Roman Catholic politicians over guerrilla
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Blair also spoke to Northern Ireland's main
Protestant politician David Trimble Tuesday but declined to give
details.
</P>
<P>
Trimble's Ulster Unionist Party, which represents many of the
province's Protestant majority, met Tuesday to discuss taking part
in the Mitchell review but reached no decision on whether to take
part in next week's review.
</P>
<P>
The party also delayed a decision on whether to seek a judicial
review of the British government's verdict that the IRA ceasefire
is still intact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
